reviewText: I ordered this DVD and Argo shortly after they became available.  This film falls short.  We all know the basics of this plot, so how these events are presented and tied together becomes vitally important to maintaining viewer interest.  This film simply presents a series of disjointed events.  I was left asking, "So what?"  There was no development of the story that leads to the conclusion.  There is also very minimal character development.  Was the real Maya this shallow?  I can't believe that Jessica Chastain was nominated for an Oscar for Best Actress.  I never experienced a suspension of disbelief in this portrayal, whether Maya is stridently admonishing a tortured terrorist suspect to "be truthful" or stridently admonishing her boss about how many days he is taking to evaluate a situation or tearfully (glycerin tears) recognizing that this phase of her life has ended and the future is unclear.  And please, my wife spent 4 years in Iraq and 2 years in Afghanistan; women do not wear Yves Saint Laurent business suits, nor even Ann Taylor, on FOBs. I had high hopes for this film and was left not really caring.

reviewText: This film has captured 5 Academy Award Nominations. I knew as soon as I heard that Kathryn Bigelow had directed a new film concerning the discovery and elimination of Osama bin Laden, I was an instant fan. You may recall she's the brilliant Academy Award winning Director of "The Hurt Locker". Again she and writer Mark Boal have created a masterpiece. This film is better (in my opinion) then "The Hurt Locker". It is because of it's subject matter and the total execution in making this entire film. I found nothing in it to complain about. It's a beautiful thing to watch in every way. This film is entertaining and fast-paced. Depicting nitty-gritty realism about the intensive search (manhunt) and discovery of one of recent history's most dangerous men, Osama bin Laden.The search for this dangerous man was on-going for over a decade. Osama bin Laden was living on borrowed time and now he is gone. "Zero Dark Thirty" does a remarkable job depicting what our American information gathering spies and agents were forced to do and go through to gather information from terrorists to find bin Laden. Violently intense, realistic scenes of torture accompany excellent acting and portrayal's of said people and actions that are painful to witness even though you know it's only actors pretending, acting out a scene. I had to keep reminding myself it's not real. The make-up used was effective and realistic looking in every way.The entire cast of "Zero Dark Thirty" has done an excellent job with all of their performance's due to their talents and it's Director Kathyrn Bigelow. Actress Jessica Chastain's performance as CIA agent Maya, has already won her a Best Actress Golden Globe Award for her part in this film. Her character Maya, who's backbone is made of steel, made strong by all her long years of hard work searching for bin Laden. Including, adding assistance during interrogation of suspected terrorist, then made stronger again when a colleague is killed. This devastating loss magnifies her desire to step-up the search for her quarry. Her character passionately believes she is the one person to find and bring down bin Laden. Religion and faith in a higher power appear in many scenes in this powerful film. Maya is shown alone, as a solitary figure throughout this film. A fact-finding sentinel that is forced many times to verbally do battle with her own superiors to complete her task which adds tension and suspense to this compelling screenplay.The extremely quiet stealth utility helicopters, the Sikorsky UH-60 Black Hawk, that are believed (no officially operating helicopters fitting this description), to have been used for the transfer of Navy Seals Team Six to bin Laden's compound to eliminate him really did sustain mechanical trouble in one of them during the operation. The team was forced to destroy it (this was not included in this film) before departing in two MH-47 Chinooks with bin Laden's remains.The hair-raising chills I experienced throughout this film were on the high side. Most of them occurring during the last quarter of this film when the Special Forces Team deploys to take out bin Laden. I believe this film affected me in this manner because I know this stories history is real and that it did affect me and every American in this country. It shows to us and the world that our country's President and military leaders will not tolerate anyone to hurt us. And if they do, retaliation definitely and swiftly will come to those who do hurt us, as soon as they (the enemy) are located. Justice will be served.Parts of this film were shot in PEC University of Technology in Chandigarh, India. Some parts were designed to look like Lahore and Abbottabad Pakistan where bin Laden was found. Locals discovered this and protested. They were insulted that their country was being made to appear as Pakistan.This films beautiful and sometimes energizing score is composed by Alexandre Desplat and is preformed by the London Symphony Orchestra. "Zero Dark Thirty" has been nominated for five Academy Awards. They are: Best Picture, Best Actress-Jessica Chastain, Best Original Screenplay, Best Film Editing, Best Sound Editing. Update: Academy Award winner for Best Sound Editing.I highly recommend this film, but it's not for the faint of heart.It is a tough film about a tough subject. Enjoy!Release date: 19 December 2012Running time: 160 minutesRated: R ~ strong violence including brutal disturbing images, and for language.American Historical drama.Grade: A
summary: "Bin Laden is there and you're going to kill him for me."

reviewText: warning, spoiler alert!on endorsing torture:the first detainee is waterboarded for not cooperating, then put in a small wood box. later, while being shown that he can be rewarded with good food, he slips up in a statement and uses the plural "we". when asked who "we" is, he refuses to answer. he is promptly threatened with torture again via an insinuation "you know what happens when you lie to me": this prompts detainee nervously giving up 3 names (you get the picture). one name is unknown to interrogator: abu akman. this is the name of bin laden's messenger. detainee is then rewarded with a cigarette. message is pretty clear, fear of more torture vs free hummus = good intel, and yes, he was eating hummus. as a side note, the CIA interrogator keeps calling detainee "bro".a second older detainee is met by the redhead female agent. she states "i had you picked up instead of killing you because you are not a violent man and don't deserve to die" (she has power of life over a non-violent prisoner because he has "deep ties" to AQ?) he says humbly, "thank you". she then states that she can keep him in pakistan or have him shipped to israel. he says "i have no wish to be tortured again, ask me a question, i can answer it.". this is the dialogue verbatim, and it really is that corny when it's delivered. then he reveals that abu akman is bin laden's "most trusted courier". another detainee doing so under implied threat of more torture, only this time it's in israel.third detainee is waterboarded before an interrogation. redhead agent then states "you do realize this is not a normal prizon, and your life is going to be uncomfortable until you give me the information i need.." then signaling the guard to hit detainee, guard punches detainee. "where exactly is abu akman living at the moment".. then he is waterboarded again. after detainee downplays identity of courier and gives up no information, she confides in colleague that the detainee is withholding that he knows abu akman, even though "we're throwing all we have at him". again waterboarding is portrayed as the key to determining the truth, this time through negative inference. he's trying too hard to act like abu akman is a nobody... even with all the goodies being thrown at him.colleague warns her that she needs to watch her back, "politics are changing" and she doesnt' want to be "left holding the bag". implication, obama is going to be president, torture will now be uncool. think of the scene where robert duval's character in apocalypse now sadly says, "some day this will all be over", without the irony.politician says "if you can't prove it's bin laden, at least prove it's not someone else, like a drug dealer", asst. director "You know we lost the ability to prove that when we lost the detainee program.. who am i supposed to ask? Some guy in gitmo that's all lawyered up??" clear swipe at the obama administration stifling the nations safety, again.movie never shows the white house's involvement in deciding to go ahead with a seal unit, instead the head of cia, gandolfini's character, seems to be the hero for taking seriously a previously unknown female agent's intuition. washington is also absent when the mission is happening.conclusion: this movie encourages the association between torture and finding the truth. it seems to have a clear political viewpoint. it encourages dualistic thought with regard to national security and human rights. but, during the last few minutes, when the OBL mission is taking place, it is entertaining and you root for the seal team. that doesn't make up for the rest of the movie.it's a g.i. joe movie for the 21st century, and this action figure has no problem waterboarding to get the bad guys.one star for the last 10 minutes.
summary: This does endorse torture and fails as an action movie.

reviewText: This movie covers a lot of territory.  It tries to put the US presence in the Middle East in a small amount of context.  Much of the dialog and information rattled off by characters in the movie can be hard to follow - unless you're well-versed in Middle East history and contemporary politics (which I'm sort of, sort of not).So there's some complexity here.  It's not an action movie.  It's not an easy movie.  Torture exists in this world.  Is it ever morally justified?  Well, that's a big question you'll have to deal with as you watch.  The movie makes the case that the US stopped using torture at some point, and I find that unlikely.  Just my inherent cynicism probably, but I just think they moved it farther underground.But that's beside the point.  This is a tense, difficult movie which I found very enjoyable.  To me this movie fits in well with Syriana and Black Hawk Down (off the top of my head) as presenting the inherent complexities and difficulties involved when the US is involved with different countries and cultures that are so vastly different than ours.

reviewText: (3/4/13, one star) From its racist overtones to its refusal to condemn torture unequivocally, Zero Dark Thirty has something to offend everyone. Senator McCain is right when he says that ZD30 gives all kinds of ammunition to the forces of radical Islam.Kathryn Bigelow portrays her fictional heroine, Maya, as a selfless patriot even though she could have walked away from torture at any time. Instead Maya stops torturing only under threat of prosecution. How heroic. How courageous. How selfless. Not.Real patriots don't torture. Torture is not only immoral but is prosecutable under both U.S. and international law for many of the same reasons that slavery and genocide are. It also causes irreparable harm to U.S. interests by radicalizing its victims and by undermining any claim we might make to moral leadership. Besides, if we didn't prosecute and condemn torturers, where would they stop? They always rationalize torture on grounds of public security, but historically have always used it as a weapon to terrorize the public and suppress political dissent.Oblivious to all these dangers and to the truth, Bigelow glorifies a fictional torturer with a broken moral compass and ignores all the very real patriotic U.S. officials who refused to torture and who were the real heroes responsible for finding bin Laden.

reviewText: A movie which puts the audience right inside the procedural shenanigans and the backdoor dealings both in the back offices and on the field while looking for the most wanted man on earth.This is a non stop thriller that deals with the obsessions of men and woman who devoted their time and sometimes their lives for tracking the man responsible for the greatest terrorist attack in the United States. Maya ( Jessica Chastain) is  one of the stars in the film. The relentless dogged pursuit of Bin Laden's courier is her obsession. Her persistence leads her colleagues at the CIA to question her credibility. `What do you think of her?', asks the CIA director (James Gandolfini). `She's smart,' answers an officer. `We're all smart,' he says.The final raid is nail biting and a cause for a big hurrah for America. The night raid scenes are acting of course but still  are filmed with a vividness that comes close to the scenes that unfolded that moonless night in Abottabad.Many people have condemned this film and the directors pro torture view. I don't think that Bigelow was trying to do that, she was reporting as a good journalist would do the actual events as they unfolded when armed with a film camera. However I feel detection and investigation played a bigger role than just torture.This is an astonishing film to watch and experience - just interesting to watch the way it all unfolds even though we all know how it ends. This is almost a three hour long movie but feels shorter because it is so well made.

reviewText: Few films made the impact that `Zero Dark Thirty' did last year.  Not only was it critically lauded (and almost swept early critics' awards, gaining early momentum for Oscar) but the controversy surrounding the treatment of certain themes and aspects of the film (mainly the torture in interrogation) made it a popular water cooler topic, and while the film would up scoring low with Oscar (a mere 5 nominations and only 1 win) it certainly deserved the attention it garnered and stands up as one of the best films of last year.Bigelow, who reignited her career with 2009's `The Hurt Locker' (winning a slew of Oscars, including one for Bigelow as director) tackles `the greatest manhunt in history' with the same nerve-racking intensity she brought to her previous effort, this time with even greater effect.  Each frame moves at a pace that allows the audience to engage directly with the atmosphere of the scene and as the scenes bleed into one another we are brought on Maya's journey into a world that constantly fights at her every push.`Zero Dark Thirty' covers the nearly ten year persistence on the part of Maya, a CIA operative who made it her life to track down and kill Osama Bin Laden.  Starting shortly after the tragic events of 9/11, Maya is sent to spearhead the investigation in Al Qaeda, and she does so with a ferocity that ultimately helps her reach her goal.  She is accompanied on this journey by others who aid her mission, but in the end it is her constant push that gets her where she needs to be.This is Bigelow's movie.  She directs it with the perfect blend of restraint and intensity.  Personally, the weakest link to this film is the performance from Jessica Chastain, who just couldn't handle the character.  I'm glad she didn't win the Oscar for this, because she fails to fully develop the woman.  I understand that the character us more of a cypher to begin with, but there was opportunity to flesh out a burgeoning passion in her eyes.  Instead, Chastain comes across very forced in her moments of conviction.  She can stare off to the side very well, but when it comes to yelling about what she wants and angrily writing on her bosses window, she comes off like a mere pretender.  The supporting cast is marvelous though.  Jason Clarke is remarkably restrained as Dan, the chief administrator of the torturous tactics, and Jennifer Ehle is so beautifully composed and natural as Jessica.  I also loved what Kyle Chandler was able to do with his character, making him feel like far more than a hot-headed boss.  It was also really cool to see Harold Perrineau in the film.At the end of the day, `Zero Dark Thirty' lives up to much of the hype.  It is a powerfully engrossing film that takes a piece of history and gives it the respect and attention it deserves.  It is in no way exploitive or tacky, but wholly realized and extremely moving.
summary: This project had a lot to prove, and it proved it!

reviewText: I walked into Zero Dark Thirty expecting a film with the heart pounding excitement of The Hurt Locker.  This film is marketed as a thriller but, it really is anything but.  Whilst I thought the final 20 minutes was clever filmmaking, the pace of the remainder of this 2.5 hour film is very dull, with almost no climatic moments.  The so called tense 'torture' scenes were just boring.  When the film started and we get underway with the story development, after an hour I remember thinking to myself 'okay.. now that the character development is complete, this will start ramping up, getting tense and heart pounding.' Er.. no.  Another one hour of arguing between the lead actress and a bunch of co-workers follows.  Sheesh.  Now, before you say I just like slam bam b-grade action movies, some of this year's best films have been slower moving dialogue driven films.  Take 'Argo' and 'Django Unchained' - fascinating dialogue driven movies, supported by great screenplays.  In Zero Dark Thirty the dialogue is just uninteresting and lacking any thrill.  In Zero Dark Thirty we get 2 hours of very slow and dull material, and then the staple 20 minute resolution.  Even the finale was not even the slightest bit thrilling.  The camera work was very good at capturing the mood (loved the handicam effect) but, there was no thrilling climax that great movies have.  The hunt for the fugitive was very matter of fact, what we know happens gets done in a very ho hum fashion, and the credits immediately roll.  What?  That was it?  That was an Oscar Best Picture front runner?  Please.  Ebert was spot-on with his review of this one.  If there's any justice, the white knuckled thriller Argo will get the nod this year -  a great example of a rare film that with almost no action present, creates a heart pounding movie simply from incredibly tense dialogue and situations.  (Although, I haven't seen the other favourite 'Lincoln' yet.)  As for Zero Dark Thirty, wait for it on dvd and rent it if you feel you absolutely must see it.

reviewText: This is top notch filmmaking.  Not a documentary, but a movie based on fact. That means the characters are composites of many people, dialogue is invented, and chronologies shifted and arranged to tell a coherent story. When all the controversy and argument is exhausted we are left with a stunning thriller based on facts but not necessarily precisely factual. This should, of course, be understood of any historical fiction.  A movie simply cannot explain everything in detail, most especially a ten year hunt for one man among billions.This is a fine film attesting to those who toil in obscurity to keep our sorry keisters safe.  Within the confines and strictures of a 2 plus hour film it tries to capture the long, arduous, lonely work of intelligence gathering, and the frustration of the search for the proverbial needle in a haystack.  I think this does so entertainingly, and that is no mean feat.The harsh treatment of detainees depicted in the beginning of the film is appropriate if it is understood in the context of the sheer panic within the relevant institutions that another attack as terrible as 9/11 or even more so was imminent. Whether the film over emphasizes this or depicts the amount and extent of time within which this took place fairly or not, I cannot answer.  It certainly doesn't sugarcoat it nor does it celebrate this treatment.  It opts to present it clearly and unflinchingly.  I do think it errs in not clarifying that after the initial panic, and even during this time, more traditional interrogation techniques were the norm.  But let there be no doubt, this was rough business with very determined and implacable foes, and I appreciated the intercutting of newsreel footage of the bombs going off worldwide while these analysts and operators were under enormous pressure to stop the carnage.Apparently, the lead to the courier that took them to Bin Laden came from several sources, and if the film leaves the impression that it was solely through harsh interrogation that it was obtained, that is unfortunate.  The film does make it clear that the final clue, the courier's real name and not his nom de guerre was found otherwise.  Anyway, this section of the film is where the controversy lies, and none of us writing here knows the real truth of it.Past that, the movie depicts the years of sacrifice of Maya, based on a real CIA analyst and probably a composite of several.  Many people spent long and fruitless hours and years in the search for Bin Laden, often at the risk of their own lives.  I think the movie fairly captures that effort.When the film gets to the raid in Abbottabad it kicks into high gear and Kathryn Bigelow's unerring knack for directing action makes a known outcome still a pulse-pounding, tense and breathless piece of business.  Extremely well done.Jessica Chastain is terrific as the dedicated analyst with apparently no social life, unsparingly sacrificing all to the mission.  Jennifer Ehle, always great, nicely represents the senior analyst that was a crucial part of this story and I was glad her & her collegues story was represented here as I recall the headlines surrounding it.  Jason Clarke, again always great, is perfect as the operator conducting the harsh interrogations with no qualms.  He plays dirty with tough customers, but it also wears on him. Mark Strong is always a reassuring and solid presence.  No fault in any of the casting.The film makes clear that the War On Terror is truly war at its meanest, nastiest and truest.  The innocent can be harmed as well as the guilty.  And as Stan McCrystal recently said, the problem with "torture" is the harm it does to the perpetrator as much or more so as to the subject in that it is a path once taken, no one can be sure where it will lead.  But to forget the context of panic and terror for those charged with our security in those days following 9/11 is I believe an unfair oversight.Zero Dark Thirty very clearly depicts a determined, hardened, ruthless, pitiless enemy and the people we charge to stop them.  It also shows the extraordinary sacrifice and determination of a few of them to hunt down and bring justice to the author of so much of this maiming, death, and heartache.  That they got Bin Laden at all is still a stunning piece of work. The movie honors that work.

reviewText: Zero Dark Thirty is a highly controversial film about finding and eventually eliminating Bin Laden.  Whether this film is based mostly on facts is up for debate but it seems that most agree it leans towards fiction for the most part.  Either way it's an entertaining film with parts that are most certainly realistic such as the public transport system bombing in England in July of '05 as well as the place where Bin Laden had apparently been hiding for years.  I imagine the parts at the end where the American soldiers invade the building at night and wipe out Bin Laden to seal the deal is nowhere near as accurate as it's portrayed in Zero Dark Thirty but for what it is (Hollywood entertainment) it's a nice fitting way to conclude a movie.  Then again when we realize that children were involved and seeing everything unfold before their eyes resulting in tears, it's really not the kind of entertainment I had in mind.For the most part the film is about a CIA agent named Jessica Chastain who is *extremely* determined to bring down Bin Laden by any means necessary.  To say she has an obsession bringing down the worlds most wanted man is an understatement.  Throughout the film she interrogates and negotiates with anyone who may know where Bin Laden's hiding, or she has her team torture and threaten anyone who has ties to Bin Laden.  To put it simply, she's a terrific actress and is easily the high point of this movie.  Otherwise most of the actors and actresses, while equally determined, are somewhat dull.While the movie thankfully never drags and while it does show us several realistic events that really did occur, unfortunately the biggest problem is that it's not 100% accurate.  Of course the movie needed to sell tickets at the movie theaters and make it Hollywood-like for the viewers to keep them focused, but Dark Zero Thirty's inability to be 100% accurate is the main reason I can't give it 5 stars.  However for 2 and a half hours, expect a lot of entertainment for your money.
summary: the darkness hour never seemed so bright

reviewText: If you want to get your USA rah-rah on, watch Argo.  Zero Dark Thirty emphasizes the zero.  First, it just plain hard to believe that with all the resources and billions available to the CIA, it took 10 years to find and kill Bin Laden. Then they "find" him in a great big obvious fortress in Pakistan with barb wire on the walls after spending years torturing miscellaneous persons to get intel.  (The torture scenes are the grittiest and most gripping parts of the movie and we Americans hate to think we employ those methods.  That is also the biggest controversy about the film.)Why not just fly around Pakistan and stake out all the suspicious fortresses first.  The "fortress" has only 3 men in it, only one of whom is armed,Bin Laden's son and UBL himself..... and about two dozen women and kids.  No disrespect to the Navy Seals.  They are highly skilled and do as told with incalculable bravery.  I thought the movie made them look bumbling. Wouldn't there have been a big effort to catch UBL alive? Noooooo, they run in the room and blow half his face off.  I don't believe the "official" version of this story and the movie made the events look even more ridiculous..I find all  the "facts" about Bin Laden's death dubious, none more so than his burial at sea.  No photos. Rush rush and hush hush.  Who was that man in the body bag?Normally, a movie fictionalizing an actual event has the leeway to add some excitement. This version just drags as did the 10 year hunt for Bin Laden.  Chastain mostly appears in multiple scenes staring at a computer and nibbling snacks....for 10 years!  Boring.  Occasionally she gets to have a little hissy fit and drop the f-bomb.  Her character is not rounded out at all in that 10 years and of course she never ages.  Basically the script and the directing is very second-rate.  I hope some day the truth comes out. Personally, I think Bin Laden died in a cave years ago and our leaders know it.

reviewText: Why you shouldn't see it:If movies that come to a slow boil aren't likely to hold your attention, there's a chance Zero Dark Thirty won't either. It covers a time period of nearly ten years, and you feel the length of the film accordingly. Each minute wears on you as time passes by with no real headway in the search for arguably history's most wanted man, and you begin to wonder whether it was all really worth all the fuss (and time... and effort... and cost...) of watching people look for him. This movie is drama much more than it is suspense, action, or anything one could remotely consider "light" (there are moments of levity, but they are more brief breaks from the slow-mounting tension than anything genuinely comical).With the main characters of this movie all being CIA and military special forces, you might expect it to be an edge-of-your-seat thriller. While there are a couple moments of thrills, the vast majority is spent wondering where the thrills ran off to. Between a moderately graphic torture scene at the beginning and a raid on UBL's compound at the end, there's mostly just a lot of talking and scheming and thinking and nerve-wearing stretching of moments.If you prefer for your movies to present you with some sort of agenda, as though Hollywood is responsible for calibrating your own moral compass, this one might not do the trick. It presents its material in a surprisingly even-handed light, which has reportedly bothered some of the more negative-minded critics out there. Since this film features depictions of distasteful acts, in the opinion of some, it is the job of the filmmaker to make obvious her distaste for said acts instead of simply portraying the story unfiltered.Why you should see it:On the surface of it, Zero Dark Thirty is, in the mold of both Argo and Lincoln this year, an expertly told historical tale. It takes an event about which most of us know many of the details and still makes it a gripping film going experience. When I take a step back and think about it, I realize that it's pretty inappropriate for me to catch myself holding my breath while watching any movie, let alone one with an ending of which I am quite familiar. And yet, that's exactly what this movie did to me, even more so than either of its historical counterparts among this year's crop of nominees.I could probably talk at length about any number of things that I consider strengths of this movie. The brilliantly understated performances of every member of the cast, not least of all Jessica Chastain, which allow the film to be driven by the slow grind of the developing plot and the atmosphere it creates. The deft and even-handed treatment of the (only partially known) source material that allows the audience to draw its own conclusions regarding both the means and the end of the hunt for Bin Laden. The distinct lack of blatant Hollywood moments used to artificially amp up the suspense of each moment, which intriguingly does much more to draw the viewer into those very moments. And, not necessarily the movie itself, but - the trailer, which perfectly conveys to the viewer exactly what to expect from the movie without spoiling any of it (I seriously love this trailer, even more than I typically love trailers, which is saying a lot).But what I really want to talk about is something else entirely. Or, more appropriately, maybe it's the combination of all of the above that leads to something that has really stuck with me as a movie-going experience I'm not used to. Now switching to explicitly first person, since it's the only voice that really seems appropriate:When I was leaving the theater, I knew that I had been made to feel something, but I couldn't quite figure out what it was. Then, as I thought back through the events of the movie, I realized that I hadn't felt "something" at all. I had felt a number of things, and those feelings had corresponded exactly with Jessica Chastain's character Maya. And, by reflection, my own feelings on the UBL manhunt itself. Ranging from discomfort to resolve to determination to jadedness to exhaustion to relief, and, as the screen went black: emptiness. I had just devoted nearly three hours of my life to watching this movie - much like the characters devoted nearly ten years of their lives to catching Bin Laden, and the closing impression we were all left with was emptiness. Not the kind of emptiness that accompanies the depressed thoughts of "why did I just watch this movie," but instead the kind of emptiness that hit Maya like a hammer when she pondered her past and wondered how that could point her to any future.In Short:To be honest, if you have seen the trailer, you should know exactly what to expect from Zero Dark Thirty (unless you're bad at watching trailers... it's not a skill everyone has). I saw in it one of the best and most evocative trailers I've ever encountered, and that's pretty much exactly the kind of movie I ended up seeing. It's subtle yet direct, clear in purpose yet uncertain in meaning. I recommend it with a 9 out of 10, because while it isn't necessarily what I enjoy about movies, it is certainly what I appreciate about them.Exceptions to the recommendation:- if you prefer your waterboarding to be in a more private setting,- people who actually enjoy the artificial, Hollywood-injected moments of suspense,- anyone hoping to see Jessica Chastain boobs,- if you don't have a leather recliner to sit in through nearly three hours of movie,- if you would rather your media present you with one slant or another so that you don't have to risk getting lost in the uncertainty of your own self-resolved morality,- if you're an Osama Bin Laden apologist.

reviewText: After hearing all the hype over this movie, I believe in fact that it is highly overrated and I doubt its historical accuracy.  There appears to be a lot of Hollywood "license" taken by the producers.  As a retired military officer, some of the unprofessional conduct displayed in this film by the CIA personnel depicted was a bit disturbing.  The female lead behaved like a spoiled adolescent brat pouting and throwing temper tantrums if she didn't get the desired actions from her superiors and the higher ups in the CIA and executive branch.  Can't believe this person got in her boss's face and wrote on his glass office window each day that no action was taken on Bin Laden.  Come on?? This was totally disrespectful, immature and unprofessional. First off, it was not his call to make.  Such decisions are made by the top leadership.  Whoever inserted this has never worked within a chain of command structure.  Can't imagine any supervisor putting up with this bratish behavior.  It also reinforced stereotypes of redheads as hot headed and out of control.  Wished the film had focused on the Special Ops community more and their preparation for the raid which deserved more film time instead of this crazy out of control lady.  The Special Operators do come off like the true professionals they are, so some credit to the film makers for that.  I like the other film version "Seal Team Six" a lot more than this one as it focuses on those who risked their lives in planning and carrying out this operation.  They are the true heroes.

reviewText: The film started with the harrowing voice recordings of the victums of 911 against a black screen.It sets the motion of American government's efforts in hunting down Bin Laden.The script writer did a painstaking job in woven the multi-stranded stories together throughoutthe unsuing 10 year period until Bin Laden's capture and execution.All the characters on both ends of the war were finely sketched, cast and acted.The several water board interrogation sequences were brutal and courageous for the filmmakers toreveal albeit some objections against its accuracy and whether it actually happened.The large cast was strongly headed by Jessica Chastian who should have been awarded this year'sBest Actress Award (not that Jennifer Lawrence did not give an eye opening performance in "SilverLining Playbook"). reviewText: There is a scene where a couple of CIA operatives are watching TV, and Obama is speaking -- I'm sure you've seen the clips -- and Obama says something like, "America doesn't torture people."  Both of the operatives stare at the TV for an extended moment, look away, and then continue talking.  And I've heard that quite a few critics wrote something like, "This movie left it up for the viewer to make a judgement about this scene."Wrong.  The operatives had a look of complete dismissal, as they should have had, which is certainly making a statement.  If you believe that the US doesn't torture to get information, then I have some oceanfront real estate to sell you in Iowa.  Every country tortures to some degree, and the US is not surely immune from it.  And there are certainly some cases where it is justified.  (If you use some simple thought experiments, and you use logic, you should quickly agree.)But is this why Kathryn Bigelow was not nominated for best direction in this film, when either the actors were simply outstanding or she deserved to win?  (I haven't seen the film where Ben Affleck won, but she definitely should have been nominated.)  But with regards to the acting, while watching you will really feel like a fly-on-the-wall spectator, hanging by unseen and listening in on extraordinary but still everyday discussions.  Just like the film "United 93" -- a film that I highly recommend watching if you haven't already -- there are almost no huge-name actors here but actors who act naturally.  That is a refreshing change, and that requires excellent direction.  It is probably easy to direct when actors overact, but requires extreme restraint to let them live in the moment.Jessica Chastain is awesome here, and you get the feeling that she is Ms. Bigelow's alter ego.  (I wouldn't doubt that Ms. Bigelow probably wanted to play the part herself if she could.)  Many films come out nowadays where you get this "strong female lead," but you know it's often just for political correctness reasons.  Not here.  Ms. Chastain kicks you-know-what and takes names, and she uses those names to find her way to Bin Laden.  She wants to kill him seemingly more than anyone on the planet, and she will not be denied.  But she plays it perfectly at the beginning, having the brains but not quite the stomach for it all, and it seems that she just learns to tolerate some things as time goes along to get her target.So you screwed up again by not nominating Ms. Bigelow for an Oscar, Academy?  What say you?  I say, "Phooey!"  And I also say, "Big recommendation on this edge-of-your-seat film."

reviewText: This movie is a great suspense film with a true story background, it tells the story of CIA agent "Maya" in the chase and capture of Bin Laden. The visuals are great and the buildup is really good in what could otherwise be a very boring film. We see the process of prisoner torture to attain intelligence, the struggle of the agents to remain sane and the difficult task of sifting through all the information they receive on a daily basis to be able to carry on their missions. I'm extremely happy that the central figure is female, and even happier that it is true! It is such an irony that some of the violent countries that engage us in conflict treat women like dirt and it is our women working along with men that will serve them justice. It is a well edited and directed film, capturing what's necessary to the story without going out in too many tangents.

reviewText: This movie was trumpeted as being historically accurate--it is not! I had high hopes for this movie, (better than the awful National Geographic movie about the killing of OBL) because of the pedigree: Katheryn Bigelow.  I found this movie to be poorly scripted, badly acted, and very poorly directed. Almost everything in the movie is fiction, overly exaggerated, with liberal use of the screenwriter's imagination.  At the end of the movie, the movie had Seal Team 6 leave from Afghanistan and return to Afghanistan.  Whom are they fooling?!?! Whom are they kidding!?!?  Early news reports reported, and later confirmed, that Seal Team 6 left from an aircraft carrier in the Arabian Sea and returned to the aircraft carrier in the Arabian Sea with OBL's body.  Aboard the aircraft carrier,the body was proved to be OBL from DNA comparison, then OBL was buried at sea in accordance with Muslim tradition. reviewText: Kathryn Bigelow won an Oscar with "The Hurt Locker" and it seems she's either fascinated with the war on terror, just really good at making movies about the war on terror, or both. I'd have to go with both. The original focus of the film was supposed to be about the December 21st battle of Tora Bora, also a film about Usama Bin Laden. When they were about to begin filming, news broke of the successful raid of the Bin Laden compound in May of 2011. Bigelow immediately shelved her Tora Bora project and redirected her focus.In this review, I'm going to do a little bit of comparison between "Zero Dark Thirty" and "Argo". They are completely different movies, but they are both historical and both are going to be mentioned a lot in the days and night leading up to Oscars. While both are factual accounts and both tried to be as accurate and true to the real events as possible, I found "Zero Dark Thirty" to be a cut above "Argo" for one glaring reason. Bigelow did not rely on Hollywood gimmicks to ramp up tension; she allowed the real events of the story do that. Affleck, with "Argo", I think did.Bigelow cast an extremely talented and fearless actress in Jessica Chastain who has been absolutely on fire since breaking onto the scene. After making her film debut in "Jolene", she continued to `wow' casting agents and landed parts in big time films like "The Debt", "The Tree of Life", "The Help", "Lawless" and "Zero Dark" among others in just three years time. Now, she is the favorite to take home Oscar for this film, and you will see why. Chastain, had to be tough as nails and vulnerable as well in order to pull off Maya. Maya is a CIA agent who spent 12-years in the agency doing one thing, tracking Bin Laden and risking everything on a thin and muddled lead that she had found Bin Laden's currier."Zero Dark Thirty" is not only incredibly accurate, it is an important piece of filmmaking that makes you question many things. The torture tactics that were used were important to finding Bin Laden, but also those tactics mixed with kindness may have played an even bigger part. The film also shows how incredibly complex and difficult it is to navigate the terror networks and as much as everybody likes to paint a yes and a no, a wrong and a right on everything done or to be done, there is nothing definitive in the war on terror."Zero Dark Thirty" is a fantastic film that I have no doubts will make Oscar voting very difficult this year and will certainly make voting for Best Actress very difficult as well. It is an important movie about history and an inside look at the intelligence battles that our agents are fighting everyday to keep us safe.
summary: HARSH REALITIES OF WAR told with truth and NO APOLOGIES

reviewText: Three years after Kathryn Bigelow, after a relatively quiet few-decade-long film directing career, really showed what she was capable of with the Iraq war masterpiece The Hurt Locker, she comes with a movie far more ambitious, and also quite a bit more controversial, about the decade long search for Osama Bin Laden from 9/11 until (no spoiler alert necessary) he was killed in a raid operation by navy seals, called Zero Dark Thirty. It absolutely lives up to, if not surpasses, her previous Oscar winning effort.Bigelow’s passion for this subject is in just about every shot, with immense detail, cold bluntness, and enough humanity to keep it from being too oppressing. Actually for a two and a half hour film it’s quite efficient filmmaking, jam-packed with numerous interrogations and investigation tactics (the torture stuff that has garnered controversy is only a very small part of that) shaking real life terrorist attacks, and political wrangling, yet it’s never confused or disjointed. Even towards the end with the recreations of the raid on the compound in Pakistan done very deliberately, the pacing is never betrayed, maintaining consistent movement and direction; it’s a scene that plays out as much mystery as suspense as the seal team goes from room to room blowing out locked doors and not knowing for certain if the main target is there.The movie’s structure, with one main character, Maya a member of the CIA played brilliantly by Jessica Chastain, taking a part in virtually every aspect of this manhunt, with other people revolving in their various tasks around her, was the perfect choice. If one person really did have this much impact on the manhunt we’ll probably never know for sure, but in this film it’s played out believably and compellingly, and though no one can match her neither is anyone else insignificant to how it plays out. Characters with only a few scenes have noticeable impacts. But with Maya is the emotion, determination, the sassiness and intelligence of a woman who evolves in nuanced but never uninteresting ways.Zero Dark Thirty is an incredible achievement, and in my mind candidate for best film made so far this decade. It has brought about an important debate, but more significantly it covers ten years of the war on terror in prime fashion. Bigelow plays for high realism but she also knows how to create great drama by stretching but never breaking those confines. Every scene belongs for a purpose and never does it feel like one is missing; that in itself is an incredible achievement. Credit her, the cast, and, not to forget, the great script by Mark Boal.Unfortunately the blu-ray is underwhelming with regards to any special features. Hopefully a more complete package comes out someday with commentary and more in-depth stuff. However the film is amazing and this blu-ray has among the highest caliber of picture and sound quality. A must buy!

reviewText: I really had no preconceived notions about this movie when I went to see it other than I'd hoped I wouldn't be flushing $10 down the toilet. What surprised me was how quickly I got sucked into this story. A prisoner is going through only what I can describe as a rough interrogation. It became quickly evident that this movie was going to portray plenty of inhumane treatment and that the people conducting these interrogations would quickly adapt to methods that were not officially sanctioned by the U.S. government but apparently practiced by the CIA and other government agencies. Quickly propelled into these interrogatory sessions is a young security analyst named Maya. Portrayed by Jessica Chastin, Maya is smart and driven and has quite a mouth on her. Recruited straight out of high school into government service, she is a driven and dedicated woman who is seen as being obsessed with locating Osama Bin Laden's whereabouts. After 9/11, it seemed as though the entire non-Arab world was trying to figure out where he was. In reality, few credible leads surfaced regarding Bin Laden's whereabouts except for plenty dead ends. However, the security community was busy with other things such as foiling terrorist attacks on the home front and foreign soil. As the movie progresses, Maya and her co-workers work a lot on the emerging threats and Maya is portrayed as hunting down Bin Laden by herself in her spare time. I found it hard not to think of Maya as a tiny vigilante working alone to bring down the giant based on the way her character is developed. As the movie progresses, world events get in the way as do government assignments and changes in leadership, but Maya perseveres with little verifiable information for her trouble. Maya finds herself thrown in harms way on a few occasions as when she gets caught in riots or when the hotel she is dining at is blown up. In the process of watching this, the viewer finds that huge bribes are offered in exchange for information and gets a sense of how information is obtained without torture.As Maya's leads begin to pay off, it becomes a waiting game regarding if and when the government plans to act. The information is circumstantial at best despite a large number of people on the ground covertly attempting to get significant information. Tension builds as the Navy Seals congregate at a desert outpost awaiting word to proceed with their daring attack which is tantalizing to the viewer but not completely explained before hand.Quite a lot of the scenes that lead up to the Seal operation to apprehend Bin Laden are interesting and provides a groundwork  as to how the intelligence community works in tandem with the military. Obviously, the part of the movie that I found most interesting was the invasion of the Bin Laden complex as the Seals scoured the property for Bin Laden. It was tense and electrifying as they moved from room to room in pursuit of the prize.  It was so intricately planned and executed that I found myself sitting on the edge of my Visually, this entire segment was really well done and justified the Seals reputation.Overall, I liked this movie. The story was told in a way that was easy to follow. The acting was good though it was clearly Jessica Chastain's trash mouth Maya who dominated this story. I thought she gave a strong performance as the tough young analyst and ultimately it was her character that drove the plot.The things that I viewed as negatives? Other than it's slow pace at times, I wasn't exactly crazy about how torture was continually being advocated, but I found myself accepting it as a necessary evil while i watched this movie play out.  The story got a little heavy handed with the premise that it was only Maya that singlehandedly cornered Bin Laden. Realistically, many other people in the security network supported this project and planned for it.I don't think this was the best picture I've seen this year, but it was a complex story that had a big payoff, featured some of the best actors you've never heard of, and had a gritty realism that was decidedly not Hollywood.

reviewText: Director Kathryn Bigelow and screenwriter Mark Boal garnered Oscars for their war film The Hurt Locker a few years ago.  While planning a film on the fruitless hunt for Al Queda leader, Osama Bin Laden, the fugitive was eventually tracked down and killed after a decade.  The filmmakers subsequently expanded their film, gathered from several first-hand accounts, and the result is Zero Dark Thirty, a thoroughly detailed, complex study in the greatest manhunt in recent history.  It is a fascinating study in the tedious work of the behind-the-scenes faceless men and women whose intelligence gathering efforts and in some cases obsessive determination culminate in the most stunning of missions.As audio of frantic, desperate victims of the September 11, 2001, terrorist attacks on the World Trade Center plays in the background, we flash forward a couple of years to the Middle East and a torture scene of an Arab prisoner witnessed by newly transplanted CIA operative, Maya (Jessica Chastain), whose intelligence is matched by her sharp tongue and dogged stubbornness.  As part of a group of operatives sifting clues and leads to locate terrorist mastermind Osama Bin Laden, she comes into conflict with  traditional, out of date methodologies.  Her theory centers on a courier who could be the link to their target, but to identify, locate and follow this suspect proves confounding and fruitless over the years as other hopeful leads fail to pan out or prove deadly. More terrorist attacks occur globally and there is a greater sense of urgency when Maya stumbles upon a crucial, misplaced piece of information.  A remarkable series of interviews in remote, secret locations and painstaking surveillance result in a possible hideout.  The question is whether to take the chance of launching a strike mission based on imperfect, yet probable data and plain, gut feelings.  What follows is a minute by minute recreation of the subsequent, military mission to end all missions.The infamous torture scenes are not so much violent as unbearable and uncomfortable.  To center on these scenes misses the point of the film.  While the story could have left out the bulk of these moments, they only serve to illustrate one of the means of collecting hard intelligence.  The film also shows the toll these acts take on the human psyche of some of the interrogators.Chastain's character is quite the rebellious analyst who is unafraid to speak her mind or display emotion.  What we don't know is her background or her family or friends.  This rough sketch of a character may serve this story adequately, but it denies the audience of more textured character development and audience empathy.  She has a deep resolve that will keep her searching for years and endless interviews often in disguise to protect her identity as she herself becomes a target, looking for the one misstep or inadvertent mention of a name or detail.  She even challenges and stands up to her superiors including the Director of the CIA (played with great effect by James Gandolfini) because of her self belief.  Hers is a female operating in essentially a male dominated profession much as Jodie Foster proves herself in similar environs in Silence of the Lambs.Bigelow excels with this intense, intricate screenplay.  She is in her element during the last half hour of the film (where there is effective use of a minimal musical score and eerie, night vision camera work) as the stealth helicopters proceed to their target and she flexes her filmic muscles, which she does as well as any action director.  John Milius (The Wind and the Lion) would be proud.As a chronicle of the remarkable mosaic of intelligence work, Zero Dark Thirty is excellent. If it lacks a little heart and soul, that's not the fault of the filmmakers so much as the source material.  While it could have easily been a thorough miniseries on television, it has been distilled to a highly engaging tale of good old fashioned detective work of the highest order. When Maya reacts to the mission's completion at the end, it is one of emotional release which the audience shares and could very well have been Bigelow's own reaction to a job thoroughly well done.
summary: ZERO DARK THIRTY and the Ultimate Manhunt

reviewText: Zero Dark Thirty spans a period of twelve years, starting with 9/11 and ending with the killing of Osama bin Laden, and the film follows the hunt for the terrorist in a surprisingly subtle, but thrilling way.  Much like Hurt Locker before it, Zero Dark Thirty is notable for the quiet moments, casual conversations over chow, for example, that explode into horrific scenes of chaos and violence.  These aren't movies interested in hundreds of soldiers invading beaches through exploding rockets and machine-gun bunkers: These are modern war films, where four bullet holes through a house's front door are enough to get the job done.In both cases, Bigelow doesn't flesh-out her main characters with obvious details, but chooses to allow the audience to understand them through their actions and reactions.  It's an engrossing effect and one that gives these characters humanity while also acknowledging that these individuals - immersed in the daily business of war - will never be fully identifiable to civilians; Jessica Chastain handles the role with ease.Pretty much a pitch-perfect demonstration of post-9/11 warfare, where intelligence-gathering and intelligent operations win the day, Zero Dark Thirty may have only one slight misstep and that is Kyle Chandler's character as the "boss who doesn't listen."  I know there are these types in real life, but here he almost stands out as an obvious cliché in the middle of a surprising group of competent characterizations.  Not the actors' fault by any means, his performance is good as always, but his constant nagging and doubts echo too many cop-show captains to give him much believably.A great film that chooses to focus on the mechanics of a sprawling manhunt without commentary or judgment, Zero Dark Thirty is simply riveting in its execution.  You will be amazed how quickly two and a half hours just flies by.
summary: Another great modern war film from Kathryn Bigelow

reviewText: Before I watched it, I thought ZERO DARK THIRTY would basically be a spiritual sequel to Bigelow's prior film, THE HURT LOCKER.  While LOCKER is a great film in many ways, it remains rather tedious and full of itself.  ZERO doesn't quite escape these shackles--it is an "important movie," after all--but it definitely ratchets up the suspense.  That's not to say it's a thriller; it's a procedural, rooted firmly in dirty politics and questionable morality.  The film basically follows one character's decade-long hunt for Bin Laden...scratch that: it follows her decade-long hunt for Bin Laden's courier.  So, you know, this isn't a Stallone film.But the movie manages to maintain a healthy pace.  This is thanks in large part to Jessica Chastain's performance; at times restrained, other moments over-the-top, she is the center of the film here, as the supporting cast (featuring great turns from Mark Strong, Joel Edgerton,  Jason Clarke, Kyle Chandler, Jennifer Ehle, James Gandolfini, and others) rotates in and out.  Mark Boal's script doesn't judge, condone, or condemn; many have viewed this movie as "pro-torture," but really, the film just puts it blatantly there: torture was used.  If the script has any major faults, it's that it's more focused on the procedural aspect; at times, we get a sense of how this obsession is affecting Chastain's character...but then we get right back to the case at hand.Bigelow's directing is solid and nuanced; I thought THE HURT LOCKER lacked any real personal touch from her, but we definitely feel it here, going from the intense opening torture sequences, through the bump and grind of office work, to the edge-of-your-seat raid at the finale (conducted in almost pitch darkness).  The film is ultimately a bit of a showoff, but it's hard to hold that against it.  Perhaps ZERO DARK THIRTY isn't the end-all be-all film that many critics hailed it as (Bigelow is one of those directors who seems to evoke the highest--and lowest--praise, with any middle ground usually passed over), but it's certainly a fine film, well-constructed and entertaining despite its at-times mundane subject matter.

reviewText: No SpoilersZero Dark Thirty (see footnote 1) is one of those movies that should win Academy Awards but probably won’t.  Oh, they will nominate it, but I would bet that most members of the Academy of Motion Picture Arts and Sciences (i.e. Hollywood types) might be a little “gun shy” of heaping awards on a movie in which American forces kill  Muslim terrorists.  Of course,  the movie is about much more than bagging Osama Bin Laden, notwithstanding the trailer.  Like Argo, this movie delves deeply (some may think too deeply) into how the CIA and politicians ultimately make the decisions culminating in a mission like this.  The result is a movie which can’t really decide if it’s a documentary or an action film.  It’s about two-thirds the former, and one-third the latter.  Not unlike how certain flavors of coffee are created.  You have to judge a cup by the overall taste and aroma, not just the various beans used.Fans of the TV shows 24 and Homeland will appreciate this blend, but anyone paying for a ticket and expecting wall to wall fast action may be disappointed.  I can assure even these folks that the last 25 minutes of the 156 minute film will deliver in spades, assuming you are still in your seat.  That 25 minutes, by the way, is almost exactly the time used by the real life SEAL team.It goes without saying that most of us know that a strike was ordered to get Osama, and that President Obama got the credit, but what we don’t know is how long and how hard many dedicated people worked to get to the moment of giving that “order”.  Over a decade of cat and mouse, pouring over cell phone recordings and emails, scanning satellite intel, checking and rechecking every tiny bit of data, chasing people around in crowded streets, interrogating suspects with methods that are OK one day and maybe criminal the next, losing people to terrorist attacks, and finally locating that one clue that leads to the jackpot.Giving a superb performance in a long and difficult role is Jessica Chastain, as Maya, who we follow from her initial recruitment into the CIA just before 9-11 through the life changing struggle of chasing down the leader of the terrorist world.  What she has to do to achieve her goal changes her forever.  We share in the burden borne by those who keep us safe while we sleep.  Likewise, I would be remiss if I did not say how a movie like this helps us all to understand and appreciate the incredible bravery and sacrifice of our soldiers and those who support them in the intelligence gathering profession.  This is Ms. Chastain’s first film of import and will certainly put her on the charts.  I also liked Jason Clark, as Dan, another CIA type who works closely with Maya in the early part of the film.  Interestingly, Chastain got the role after the first choice, Rooney Mara (Lisbeth in the Girl With The Dragon Tattoo), had to drop out.The music is very good, and for some reason the name Alexandre Desplat did not register, but he also worked with this director on Argo and he did other things you know:  Extremely Loud and Incredibly Close, The King’s Speech, Harry Potter and the Deathly Hallows Pt 2, Twilight Saga: New Moon, and Syriana, to name just a few.  He has done so many, you have surely seen one or more of his movies.  I never really noticed the soundtrack (which is good) but at times it amplified what I was seeing, so kudos to Mr. Desplat for this one.The director, Kathryn Bigelow, is very good at her job and quite attractive to boot (check out her publicity photo).  Why James Cameron gave her up is a mystery to me.  She has made some very interesting movies including The Hurt Locker, Point Break, K-19 The Widowmaker, and Strange Days.  I’ve seen them all.  Her quote is “You cast not for marquee value but for performance and talent. The right actor for the part. Anything else is a compromise.”  I would have to agree with that.  And there really aren’t any in this film who are marquee status.  That works well, because a big name actor would probably have been distracting.  An example you ask?  James Gandolfini makes a brief but memorable cameo.  I love that guy, but I was distracted enough to poke my wife and say “It’s Tony Soprano in the White House!”Having given credit to Ms. Bigelow, I would like to spend a moment on the cinematography.  If you have read my reviews, you know my pet peeve is the “unsteady” cam, in which it appears the camera man or woman is in a state from slight to severe inebriation.  This movie falls into the “slight” column, because most shots seem to be wobbling around just a bit when there is no need for it.  However, it was not nearly as bad as my all time #1 carsick poster child: District 9 (followed closely by some of the Bourne movies).  This type of camera work began with TV series like Law And Order, and was supposed to make the viewer feel as if what he or she is watching is real (like home movies I guess).A caveat for the squeamish.  As with my prior review of Django, I caution those who are easily upset by scenes of “mild” torture.  While there is no actual “waterboarding” here, similar tactics are employed, and the film spends a good deal of time showing how detainees are “persuaded” to talk.  I felt the movie spent too much time on this aspect, but you be the judge and please leave a comment.  The debate about how far we should go to obtain information that can save lives is ongoing.  I will just say that if my family was threatened, I would want them to go pretty far.  In an interesting and unusual “reply” by the CIA (quoted from IMDB):  Acting CIA Director Michael Morell issued a statement about the film emphasizing that while the production team had met with the CIA, the film is a dramatization and is not historically accurate. Morell specifically contradicted the film's assertion that "enhanced interrogation techniques" also known as "torture", had been of significant benefit in locating Osama bin Laden. Director Morell stated, "That impression is false. We cannot allow a Hollywoodfilm to cloud our memory."  So there you go.Unlike Argo, the ending did not lend itself to applause, but I think the writers wanted to leave us with the message that there are no winners in this type of ongoing war, only those who won today.Footnote 1: (from IMDB) "0 dark 30" is a term commonly used by the military to refer to a non-specific time when it is dark outside, either very late or very early. However, the prevailing pronunciation is "oh dark thirty".
summary: You can run but you can't hide from Seal Team 6

reviewText: Zero Dark Thirty, which is military talk for 12:30 AM, tells the story of the hunt for Osama bin Laden (about two-thirds of the movie), as well as his eventual take-down (the final third of the movie).  So while it features Navy SEALs in the final act, the real focus is on the intelligence agents who who pursued UBL with dogged determination for more than ten years, particularly Maya (played with intensity by Jessica Chastain).The film won a slew of awards in various categories, including best picture, best director, best actress, best screenplay, best editing and others.  It was also nominated for many awards, including the Academy Award for Best Picture (it lost to Argo).The blu-ray transer is what one would expect for a recent release--excellent picture and sound--with one exception.  The bin Laden take-down was done at night, and Kathryn Bigelow mimics nighttime conditions as much as possible.  This did not work so well on my TV at home.  The picture was so dark that I had to eliminate all ambient light in the house in order to make out what the SEALs were doing.  I did not remember the movie being that dark when I saw it in the theater.Parental Advisory: This is not a movie for children.  It features torture portrayed in a realistic manner.  This is very difficult to watch even for a guy like me who is used to war movies.  The movie also contains a realistic battle scene at the end of the movie, where people are shot and blood is spilled.  There is also strong language, alcohol, explosions, shootings, etc.  Parents would need to judge whether their high school students could handle it.  I would not recommend it for junior high or below.  Even some adults with sensitive consciences may be bothered.I highly recommend Zero Dark Thirty.  It is a piece of history that will live in the memories of those of us who witnessed the events of 9/11.  This movie manages to maintain suspense, even though you already know how it turns out in the end.

reviewText: 'Zero Dark Thirty', which is common military slang for, essentially, going operational when the rest of the world is sleeping is the rare film that neither glorifies nor indicts it's subject matter. But overall, this is a riveting tale told beautifully.Forget the politics and just absorb the gripping narrative...

reviewText: My first reaction to Zero Dark Thirty was that it was a near-great film but that it wasn't great because it didn't show that the people who do this work (relentlessly torture, hunt, and kill people) must be able to shelve their own lives/humanity for the time it takes them to accomplish their mission. This film does everything so well that it seemed a shame that director Kathryn Bigelow didn't show that Maya (Jessica Chastain) was in any way conflicted or troubled about the torture she witnessed and allowed. But then it occured to me that the people who do this kind of work do it precisely because they are not conflicted about it.  One of Maya's black ops co-workers, Patrick (Joel Edgerton), at one point decides to get away ftom the torture facility and go back to Washington, however, this is not because of any crisis of conscience, but simply because he wants to try something else for a while. So this refusal to show either Maya or Patrick as in any way conflicted about their work is actually the boldest choice Bigelow makes with this film. The people who do this work, especially Maya, are no-nonsense types and Bigelow's no-nonsense style foregrounds that quality. I don't think we can really tell by watching this film just what Kathryn Bigelow's politics might be and so they are never a distraction. I enjoyed Argo quite a lot, but saw this the day after I saw Argo and there is no comparison. Argo consistently entertains, but Zero Dark Thirty will blow you away (regardless of your politics). My revised opinion of this film is that it is a great film. Probably the only reason it didn't win any major awards is because the movie doesn't exactly condone torture but it doesn't condemn it either, it remains neutral so that you can decide for yourself how you feel about it. And this makes some viewers (who are used to being told how to feel---with music and other cinematic devices)feel uncomfortable and uncertain (which is what Bigelow wants). But don't take my or anyone's word for it, just see it. You won't be sorry.

reviewText: If you are interested enough to consider seeing ZERO DARK THIRTY in the first place, you will almost certainly find it worthwhile. Just pick a time when you have 2.5 hours and a good bit of patience to spare. The acting, script, and cinematography are all quite good, and Jessica Chastain gives a strong performance as CIA Agent "Maya," generally quiet and low-key but utterly driven in her pursuit of high-level Al-Queda operatives and ultimately, Osama Bin Laden himself.Two problem areas:--Pacing: The first half shows a lot of CIA interrogations, coercion, and bit-by-bit uncoverings of details over the course of eight years. The key events toward the end all happen a little too quickly, and consequently, it seems, too easily. It also stops short in some crucial spots: I don't want to spoil anything, but I think you'll see what I mean. It's entirely possible that the producers were in a hurry to get this out while the events were still fresh on people's minds, hence the lopsided feel of the film. ZERO DARK THIRTY's creators had a long, hard story to tell, but nevertheless, it seems they could have found some ways to add excitement.--Scope: Perhaps intentionally, in order to show the arduous process the CIA went through, there aren't a lot of changes in scenery here. Most of ZERO DARK THIRTY takes place in various CIA headquarters and interrogation rooms. Certain key political and military figures are conspicuously absent, omissions that I'm sure were made because of the recency of these events and a desire to avoid politicization. Still, more of an overview of the roles that other U.S.  agencies, America in general, Pakistan, and the rest of the Middle East played here would also have made this a better film.I haven't done any fact-checking, but as oversimplified as parts of this film are, I'm sure it has some major inaccuracies; e.g., Just who IS "Maya" anyway? Does she have a last name?Yet, for all my quibbles, I found ZERO DARK THIRTY riveting, as I think most American audiences will find it, and am glad to have seen it. A few years down the road, when these events are more history and less current news, I hope that someone will make a more detailed and all-inclusive dramatization of the hunt for bin Laden.
summary: How Could It Not Be Fascinating?

reviewText: ZERO DARK THIRTY is a very well-made film; cleverly photographed, well told, with a stunning central performance from Jessica Chastain as a CIA operative possessing both the determination and the sheer persistence to fulfill her quest to catch Osama Bin Laden.  The job is not always successful - along the way she loses colleagues and  friends, the victims of terrorist bombs and/or unexpected attacks.  Nor does she obtain full co-operation from her (mostly male) superiors, who seem more concerned with feathering their own reputational nests rather than accomplishing the job in hand.  However, I do have to admit that the film's structure - the us-versus-them notion, with numerous sequences showing the CIA operatives tracking their prey, as well as spying on one another - is a familiar one, dating from the Cold War films of the Sixties and early Seventies.  Only this time the enemies are not the Soviets, but those working for Al-Quaeda.  Other clichés also prevail, including the passing of secrets in dark places, the use of extended long shots following characters walking along corridors, and the final sequence consisting of an extended raid on the Bin Laden lair.  Nonetheless the film is quite entertaining, if somewhat lengthy.
summary: Cold War Thriller Transposed to the post-9/11 Era

reviewText: WARNING: I've read all the controversy about the depiction of torture in this movie, and the indignant responses from the authorities. I'm not going to judge it on those grounds -- this is strictly artistic.A few years ago, Kathryn Bigelow made a little movie called "The Hurt Locker" -- a raw, grimy, unromanticized look at bomb-disposal soldiers in wartime Iraq. It made her the first woman to ever win a Best Director Academy Award.So she seems like the perfect choice for a much more epic story: the tale of how Special Ops and the CIA finally hunted down and killed Osama bin Laden. It's filmed and directed in the same hyper-realistic manner as "Hurt Locker," but it's clear from the beginning that this is a story with much higher stakes, with repercussions spanning whole countries.As the story opens, a young CIA agent named Maya (Jessica Chastain) is overseeing the interrogation/torture of al Qaeda prisoners in Pakistan. She learns of a man referred to as Abu Ahmed, who is the personal courier to bin Laden -- and with fierce determination, she sets out to locate this man so she can get bin Laden through him. Even when the man is reported dead, she never wavers in her determination.Over the years that follow, Maya survives being shot at, bombed, the loss of her friend and a change in administration that may ruin her career. With the help of her friend Dan (Jason Clarke), she follows the intel to a fortress-like compound in Pakistan, where the CIA soon realizes bin Laden is hiding. As the months roll by, Maya pushes for a night raid on the compound -- and when the raid goes through, the soldiers bring the decade-long hunt to its bloody conclusion."Zero Dark Thirty" has its fair share of fictional characters (Maya) and scenarios (waterboarding), but to be honest, it doesn't FEEL like a movie. There are no "stirring" moments, no melodramatics, no rousing speeches, no swell of an orchestra when something important happens. When the final raid on the compound finally happens, it's not a bombastic action sequence, but a slow-moving affair punctuated by blasts of gunfire and the screams of children.Instead, it feels more like you're trailing after the CIA agents and soldiers, through the sun-drenched, dusty Middle-Eastern cities. Most of the story simply follows Maya as she chases clues, rumors and phone numbers, and it takes her YEARS to actually get some decent results.Nothing happens fast. Time rolls by slowly, full of slow progress and frustrating setbacks -- just look at the scenes where a furious Maya scribbles numbers on her boss's window. For most directors, this slow pace and attention to realistic detail would probably end up being boring, but the sudden violent attacks by al Qaeda -- leaving innocent people dead, bloody and screaming -- reminds you WHY the characters have been chasing bin Laden for so long.Unfortunately, some of the dialogue is hokey. Exhibit A: "What part convinced you?" "Her confidence." That is some cheezy blockbuster dialogue, and does not fit in a movie filmed in such a realistic style.But despite that drawback, Bigelow draws quietly intense performances from all the actors, particularly Jessica Chastain. Apparently Maya isn't based on anyone in particular -- she's just a sort of generic CIA woman, but the ethereal-looking Chastain gives her an iron skin and flinty eyes. Her armor doesn't crack until her mission is over.And there are a lot of great performances by the rest of the cast. Clarke gives an unflinching performance as a cold, jaded soldier who regains some of his fire due to Maya's determination, along with Reda Kateb, Harold Perrineau, Kyle Chandler, and especially the underrated Jennifer Ehle as a bright-eyed, equally determined friend of Maya's."Zero Dark Thirty" is one of those movies that can almost convince you it's real, despite the chunks of hokey dialogue. The powerfully understated acting and realistic direction carry you along to the end of the quest.

reviewText: "Zero Dark 30" is an account of the CIA's decade-long hunt for Osama bin Laden, culminating in the raid on his compound in Pakistan. Jessica Chastain portrays Maya, a red-haired beauty who initially appears fragile and vulnerable. As time passes, she toughens up, uses four-letter words liberally, and spits out her opinions when she is angry (which is often). Maya is obsessed with locating and killing Bin Laden, whom she calls UBL. She and her colleagues follow up every lead, no matter how flimsy, since even a courier could be the key to discovering UBL's hiding place.Kathryn Bigelow has garnered a great deal of criticism in the wake of this movie's release. First, there are the infamous scenes in which CIA operatives transport detainees to "black sites," where the captors beat their prisoners repeatedly; deprive them of sleep, food, and drink; pour water over their faces to simulate the feeling of being drowned; and string them up by their wrists. Bigelow asserts that she does not personally endorse torture as a means of obtaining information. Furthermore, she insists that although the movie is based on actual events, she uses artistic license to tell her story.Is "Zero Dark Thirty" worth seeing? Yes, for a number of reasons, including the edgy screenplay by Mark Boal, Greg Fraser's superb cinematography, Jeremy Hindle's impressive production design, and Alexandre Desplat's evocative score. Bigelow's direction is gutsy, fast-paced, and powerful. There are no opening credits, just a dark screen with the sounds of 9/11 assaulting our senses. She then segues to the infamous and grisly torture sequences, but leaves it to us to decide whether such extreme interrogation methods can ever be morally justified.Jessica Chastain shines as a brittle and hot-tempered individual who, as far as we know, has no friends, family, or outside interests to distract her from her grim and difficult task. Jason Clarke, another CIA operative, taunts and torments detainees, but is smart enough to realize that he harms himself by engaging in such tactics. Reda Kateb is excellent as a stubborn captive who does his best to withstand degradation and pain in his determination to protect his secrets. James Gandolfini is fierce and savvy as former CIA director Leon Panetta; he demands proof of Osama bin Ladin's whereabouts, and is not content with probabilities and suppositions. Kyle Chandler, Maya's stressed-out boss, knows that he will take the fall if things go belly-up.This provocative film demonstrates how difficult it is to glean solid intelligence concerning potential terror attacks. Monitoring emails and telephone calls; following the wire transfers of known jihadists who need a steady supply of funds; and conducting video surveillance to monitor the movements of people of interest may yield useful data. However, analysts such as Maya, who are experienced in the ways that terrorists think and behave, also play a crucial role. It is fascinating to see how the changing political winds in Washington influence the CIA's policies. Finally, the takedown of Bin-Laden by Seal Team Six is mesmerizing. "Zero Dark Thirty" invites us to discuss some of the toughest dilemmas that face us as a democratic society under siege.
summary: "When you lie to me, I hurt you."

reviewText: Zero Dark Thirty was solid. If you are intrigued by the CIA and how it gathers intelligence, you will throughly enjoy this movie. Don't be intimidated by the length of this movie - it moves briskly and keeps your attention throughout.The movie follows Jessica Chastain's character as she turns over every rock to find America's worst enemy.
