If you haven't seen it yet, it should definitely be near the top of your list. Entertaining (you will not want to leave your seat until the credits roll), intriguing (feels like you are getting an inside look at how the CIA gathers its intelligence, how the US executes missions, etc), and a great production (five Oscar nominations). It's not the best movie ever made, but so as you are not expecting it to be, you should not be disappointed.

reviewText: I confess, I went to see this film because of the hype, and because the trailer hinted at an expose of the back story that went into the killing of UBL. I am happy to report that this movie exceeded my hopes and expectations. If you want to get a close, documentary, indie-style look at what happened, this movie will probably meet or exceed your expectations as well.That said, the first half hour of the film is not for those who do not like to see their real-world violence up-close and personal. However, if you seem well-suited to the film and its genre in every other respect, then my advice is to see it, and use your eyelids early and often as you see fit... and know that there isn't anything gory or gruesome that jumps into your face without warning.The only (very minor) shortcoming is that I would have liked to know why the CIA recruited Maya (the lead around which Hollywood got the focal point needed to tell this story) OUT OF HIGH SCHOOL. The movie makes that point clear, but goes out of its way to avoid answering the question. In the film, she is bright and tenacious without being portrayed as a savant. Leaving why she was picked up just out of H.S. in question is irrelevant to the overall tale while including it would have added a small amount of depth to a character that is otherwise not overly developed.
summary: Fast-Paced, Well-Acted, Realistic Enough, Interesting Throughout...

reviewText: This film was okay; not good, not bad, just mediocre. The first quarter starts off with an anti-ordinary scene (normally seen in Hollywood dramas about terrorism) during which the CIA interrogates and tortures, as well as kindly feeds, a "terrorist" (he's kindly given a cigarette after his meal). "Zero Dark Thirty" is similar to all of M. Knight Shyalaman's movies because they both were slow with dragged-through-the-mud drama that bored me, although the "suspenseful" moments of explosions did wake me up. This film is not what you normally expect and see in Hollywood "terrorist" movies. What was interesting about the way the story was told was the process the main character, Maya, goes through (as well as the other CIA agents) about the agonizing, slow, but purposeful hunt for "UBL". It doesn't shoot like a typical Hollywood movie (e.g. "True Lies"), but rather takes its time (take too much time) in developing the story and "chase" for the main terrorist. However, there were many negatives about this film that made many film critics question its Oscar worthiness. For example, when Maya leaves a compound in her car, she is confronted by terrorists who calmly start shooting at her vehicle. How does Maya react? She just ducks in her car without screaming or driving away and panicking (like a normal person would do) for several seconds until she finally puts the car in reverse and returns safely to the compound. That's not reality. Another negative is the way the closing scenes were filmed and shot (i.e. camera angles and lighting) when the military invades "UBL's" fortress. The way the scenes are black is understandable (afterall, it is night time), but rather bothersome and disorienting. What would have been better is if the scenes were shot in first-person point-of-view (i.e. from the viewpoint of any one of the military personnel that were part of the "UBL" fortress invasion and kill (i.e. in "night vision" mode) to make the scenes watchable and so we, the viewers, know what the hell is going on.Anyway, the fact that this film was nominated and won some Hollywood awards is quite ludicrous. If you're interested in watching a better film, watch "Battle for Haditha", which was more dramatic, disturbing, emotional, and graphic. Note: Just because a movie does not get nominated for a stereotypical Hollywood award and/or does not have popular/famous actors, actresses, directors, and producers, does not mean it's not worth seeing or is not a good movie (case in point, "Battle for Haditha"). I'm sure there's going to be some reviewers who will disagree and moronically say "Zero Dark Thirty was an excellent film" (uneducated dissidents will always be there to criticize the intelligent).

reviewText: I knew that this movie began with scenes of torture, but I didn't expect it to go on and on for pretty much the first hour of the movie. And I didn't expect it to be basically irrelevant to the actual plot. The amount of violence in this movie seemed over the top to me. I know terrorist interrogations are not a Sunday School picnic, and I know the CIA and SEALS are not boy scouts on a walk in the woods. But I felt worn down by the constant violence. The actual discovery of where bin Laden was hiding was obscured by the over-emphasis on interrogating people who knew little or nothing.This movie raises more questions than it answers. Sitting in the audience, I saw and heard and felt a helicopter crash and numerous explosions as the team invaded the compound--but bin Laden himself was apparently in a coma or something, because he never even picked up the gun he kept over his bed. The lack of any defense at a compound hiding the man who supposedly killed thousands of people, his failure to make any move to protect his wife and kids, strains belief. But by the time you get to that, you have been bludgeoned into submission by a constant stream of torture and explosions and gunfire.The writer and director made many odd choices here. The acting was good, but the choices of what to show and what to leave out were peculiar. Much more attention to threads that led nowhere, and very little understanding of how they actually found bin Laden. Disappointing.
summary: Too many loose ends, too much torture

reviewText: 'Zero Dark Thirty' is a very fine film....  And is worth a viewing; or several.  However---it does imply that torture Was a successful way of acquiring information in the 'war on terror.'  That may not be evident at first.  But it's true.  It does suggest that one person who is willing to sacrifice Everything in her life for a single end can make a difference----at terrible emotional and personal sacrifice to herself ---that point is only settled towards the very end of the movie.  The movie abstracts from the question of the network and network of networks of 'terrorists' who were left alive after the successful raid against Bin Laden.  And it abstracts from any question involving Bin Laden's links to Afghanee operations against the Soviets; and of his connection to and hatred of the Saudis and his family in Saudi Arabia; and of his displacement of this hatred towards the United States; it abstracts too from the fact that the United States had him 'cornered' near the Pakhistani border (but turned the operation over to the Afghanees---guaranteeing his escape (note: that was to have been the theme of an earlier project by the director and script writer of this film abandoned after the successful raid set forth in this film).  Perhaps those themes will be explored in some other film?????  Still---this is a fine film.And Jessica is superb.  Let's hope that the film industry finds her parts worthy of her unlimited talent.Sincerely, Dr. Frank Braio

reviewText: If I want to watch a digital copy of my movie on a computer, it is when I'm on the road on business or for vacation. That means Internet probably is not available for streaming. But don't advertise Ultraviolet as a digital copy, because it is not. reviewText: I should have liked this movie. I have enjoyed many movies in this new "War of Terror" genre that American filmmaking has opened up post-9/11. The success of 24 (okay, more a TV series) was kind of the origin of this genre, United 93 was simply one of the most gripping movies I"ve ever seen, period, Steven Spielberg's Munich was also very good, and the director of this movie, Kathryn Bigelowe, previously worked on the excellent Hurt Locker.There have also been some duds. Green Zone was a pretty big dud in my book. A shame, since it was made by the same team who made the very gripping United 93.And add this movie to the dud list.Off the bat, my biggest problem was that I knew what happened. There is never any doubt as to the final outcome. We know that Bin Laden was killed in a raid by Navy Seals. Beyond that though, many of the fundamental resting points of the plot I knew the outcome already. For instance, in one pivotal (SPOILER) scene, the CIA thinks that it had turned a Bin Laden lieutenant to their side. The guy arrives in the base, and blows them up with a bomb. It is a big betrayal, which was supposed to be a down "all hope is lost" moment in the movie. Except, I already knew that had happened, so I knew that he was a bomber. It was in the New York Times and I remember reading the article myself.(/SPOILER).You could argue the same applies for United 93. Yet, at least for me, United 93 was far more gripping, even though I knew the outcome, because --1. I was not overly familiar with the events of 9/11. I had no reason to. I, and most educated viewers, are likely broadly aware of the outline of the War on Terror. This film relies on several pivots of the actual War on Terror to alter the mood of the film. But these pivots are not a surprise if you've kept up with the news.2. United 93 was a loss. There is an underdog in the movie, and it is the passengers of the civilian plane. In this movie, you have the intelligence unit of the world's most powerful military, with the greatest killing power ever known on Earth at her disposal. Zero Dark Thirty is about an Empire swatting flies, not ordinary people struggling in an event wildly out of their control.On that note, Zero Dark Thirty is also inferior to Hurt Locker for precisely that reason. Hurt Locker was about the grunts on the ground. This movie is about a jet-setting bureaucrat. Sure, she sweats and frets in her office, and occasionally a terrorist gets close to her, broadly, but, she spends most of the time in a secure office, with the tools of a global-spanning empire at her disposal, not in the dangerous field. Stakes are higher when at stake is your actual arms and legs, not an Imperial abstraction. Hurt Locker did an especially good job of throwing the viewer off with an (SPOILER) early death (/SPOILER), and more broadly Hurt Locker succeeded because the drama of the film centered around a group of people who we know performed a very risky job, whose universe is small enough that the final outcome is in doubt. There is doubt that the heroes in Hurt Locker will survive because we know for a fact that men who served in Iraq suffered many casualties. The final outcome of Hurt Locker is a mystery. The final outcome of Zero Dark Thirty was blasted on the news several years ago, and was a big deal.So, it was a bore. I did not really feel for the protagonist. Because while I can imagine myself becoming a soldier in the Army, or being a hapless civilian on a flight gone horribly wrong, I can't really imagine myself as an elite CIA intelligence officer. All in all, I felt that there were actually many missed opportunities in writing this movie. I also feel that the central story of this would have been better handled as a fantasy allegory, where many of the themes are similar, but the broader universe is one constructed by the writer and not ripped from the headlines.

reviewText: I saw this first in the theater and had to have to Blu-ray to view it at home. This is not a movie for the squeamish. The scenes of torture are graphic and, I believe, very realistic. But, underlying all that is the intricate story of how the US tracked down the biggest criminal of our time and brought him to justice. I thought everyone in this picture did a credible job of portraying what actually happened (as far as we know from media reports and what the government will tell us). There is no doubt in my mind that we are in a war which our enemy intends to win and will never stop trying. The death of Osam Bin Ladin did not and will not stop it. This story, while it may seem to be an ending, is not and there will probably be more tales like this for God knows how many more years. But, this picture was a well-acted and vivid portrayal of what the men and women working to protect us and avenge us are going through.

reviewText: ZERO DARK THIRTY is a powerful film. Its subtle brilliance is evident on many levels. It is somewhat episodic, yet the narrative flow is dynamic and extraordinarily cohesive and the energy exuded is raw and energetic.  It is a story of seeking out the diabolically enigmatic elusive Osama bin Laden and what it took in time, efforts, lives and resolve to bring him to an end. Always just below the surface is the perseverance, against seemingly insurmountable odds, of Jessica Chastain's Maya. Jessica Chastain's performance is one of relentless determination to bring bin Laden's comeuppance to fruition.  For me this was a riveting film that started at a slow and deliberate pace, but gradually built to an intense and intelligent conclusion.  It is beyond my expectations.

reviewText: The 2012 Best Picture lineup--let's face it--hasn't been all that impressive.  I have seen six of the nominated films--no interest in seeing Amour, Silver Linings Playbook or Beasts of the Southern Wild--and the only ones of those two that I thought were any good were Argo and Django Unchained.  Zero Dark Thirty, is my most recent viewing of a Best Picture nominee, and needless to say, Act of Valor was a much superior film in every way (and that is no insult to AoV either, since it is a much better film that what most people give it credit for).And to quickly establish myself here, I am quite fond of Kathryn Bigelow as a filmmaker.  Point Break remains one of my favorite films of 1991, and one of my favorite films to star either Keanu Reeves or Patrick Swayze.  And The Hurt Locker was most certainly one of the three or so best films of 2008, and one of the four better choices to select for Best Picture in 2009, along with Inglourious Basterds, A Serious Man, and Up in the Air.  So, after I heard that Kathryn Bigelow wasn't going to try to connect any dots to our current occupent as a means of praising him for the death of Osama Bin Laden, I was willing to give this one a shot.And boy, is this film a letdown.  Jessica Chastain does a great job playing static and robotic, without much of a character beyond her career-long obsession with finding and killing Osama Bin Laden.  Understandably, Bigelow directed her to play it subtle to the enth degree.  But as a consequence, she is boring.  The film is over 150 minutes long.  The history behind the manhunt as it was retold to us is astronomically uninteresting.  Whereas a film like A King's Speech benefited from the lack of information on what really happened during King George's therapy sessions, this film clearly didn't have the classified intel critics were going ape$#!+ over, and did very little to nothing to help matters much.  The hunt lasted for about 10 years or so.  We heard very little of went on behind the scenes if anything at all.  And there was literally nothing Bigelow had done to try to make it exciting, intense, or interesting.  Well, until the very end when she finally tracks down where he is hiding and sends some soldiers down there to find and execute him.It's a boring 2 hour exercise with an interesting beginning and a thrilling ending.  So much could have been trimmed because the film as a whole just doesn't work.  But out of respect on the film's strongest assets, I'm willing to give this film a 4 out of 10.  I can't condemn it, but neither can I recommend this one.  I wish I could.  That translates to a 2 out of 5 by Amazon standards.
summary: Unfortunately, it is Yet Another Best Picture Nominated Disappointment

reviewText: Controversy is the main reason this film garnered so much attention in and out of the theaters. Controversy and curiosity and a degree of voyeurism. It probably is important that ZERO DARK THRITY was made: the film does help assuage the anxiety that tore through this country following the infamous 9/11 and subsequent acts of terrorism and if it helps bring closure to that decade of fear and loathing that intervened before the ultimate capture and killing of Osama bin Laden then it is worth placing before the public. By definition, the movie is 'a chronicle of the decade-long hunt for al-Qaeda terrorist leader Osama bin Laden after the September 2001 attacks, and his death at the hands of the Navy S.E.A.L. Team 6 in May 2011.'Many aspects of the action that takes place through this nearly three hour long film is unexplained: the meaning of the title of the film we can look up as `"ZERO DARK THIRTY is a military term for thirty minutes after midnight - as well as code for "under the cover of darkness." It is also the time that the Navy Seals helicopters took to the skies on their mission to eliminate the world's most wanted man [Osama bin Laden]. Finally, it serves as a metaphor for the decade long, relentless pursuit of Osama bin Laden". Mark Boal wrote the screenplay for director Kathryn Bigelow and together they condensed activity of 10 years well. The cast is uniformly fine (it is interesting that very few critics singled out the astonishingly credible performance of Reda Kateb as Ammar, the brutally tortured focal point of the film's interrogation techniques) and of course Jessica Chastain manages to make us understand the obsession of Maya as the almost solitary person who insisted on finding and killing bin Laden. She plays the CIA operative whose first experience is in the interrogation of prisoners following the Al Qaeda attacks against the U.S. on the 11th September 2001. She is a reluctant participant in extreme duress applied to the detainees, but believes that the truth may only be obtained through such tactics. For several years, she is single-minded in her pursuit of leads to uncover the whereabouts of Al Qaeda's leader, Osama Bin Laden. Finally, in 2011, it appears that her work will pay off, and a U.S. Navy SEAL team is sent to kill or capture Bin Laden: only Maya is confident Bin Laden is where she says he is.The others in the cast are also excellent - Jason Clarke, Kyle Chandler, Mark Strong, Jennifer Ehle, Harold Perrineau, Mark Strong, James Gandolfini, Stephen Dillane, Joel Edgerton et al - but the problem this viewer has with the film is that the characters never become identifiable people and remain tropes. Another problem with the On Demand version and the DVD is that on a small screen the dialogue I so covered with extraneous noise and overlapping of lines that subtitles become necessary - and they don't function! The film is far too long (acknowledging that part of the director's intent was to show how LONG 10 years of hunting was) and it is only in the last hour that the movie `catches fire' and hold our attention.  Time will likely allow us to know if people who watch this confusing and interminable study of the decade of pursuit will understand it. The film does place before our eyes some of the uglier aspects of war (on both sides) and it is well to be reminded of that aspect of our endless unwelcome presence in the Middle East.  Grady Harp, March 13

reviewText: This is NOT a "high-voltage thriller". It's actually quite tedious.For most of the movie, you will be watching a police procedural. Some torture at the beginning may be the most interesting part; the raid at the end is mostly in too much darkness. The rest:  investigation, investigation, investigation, punctuated by a couple of explosions.The heroine, Maya, becomes insufferable. Yes, she's obsessed with finding "UBL". But she becomes horribly arrogant, telling the SEAL team "You're going to kill him for me." It's one thing to make her a bad-a**; here they overreached. After that line, I couldn't take her seriously anymore, and I didn't care about her character. Except for finding her contemptible. Near the last third of the movie she is put on such a high pedestal and praised so much - super smart, super confident, etc. etc., it's frankly quite nauseating.In another part we are treated to watching a Pollyanna-ish agent (different woman - are there really that many women in the interrogative services?) getting giddy about meeting and interviewing a potential lead, terribly endangering the people around her by insisting on relaxing security measures. Some tragedies ... are avoidable.It is interesting watching them track the cell phone user who leads them to UBL, near the end. But the raid, as I said, is botched - it's usually too dark to see what's happening, except for the night vision parts. I tried different settings on my TV, and it didn't help much.And they didn't show UBL using his wife as a human shield. A strange omission.Speaking of omissions, one character says that "the President is a thoughtful, analytical man." So thoughtful, in fact, that he took 13 or so hours to decide to give the go ahead, and then only after he had crafted a document to sign that absolved himself of all blame in case anything went wrong. (The blame would fall upon the military.) They left that part out. Strange.I will probably be selling my copy. Maybe that's why Amazon's not letting us sell them yet? (Like Argo.) RENT AT REDBOX (or something comparatively cheap) FIRST to see if you want to buy. I wish I had.
summary: Very disappointing, slow, tedious, terrible heroine

reviewText: From a filmmaking POV ZERO DARK THIRTY and THE HURT LOCKER are crafted by a genuine filmmaker who brings a documentary type narrative to a highly controversial film that is ZDT. The film starts off with a highly disturbing interogation/torture scene that goes on for a lenghty time in finding crucial intell to the whereabouts of highly placed terrorists. One might say after 9/11 America's moral compass had become warped when it came to finding leads in the whereabouts of terrorists and potential terrorists. As for me I've always believed torture had been sanctioned throughout American history in the fight during the Cold War and Vietnam to the present day. The USA might say it doesn't sanction torture but any self-respecting and educated person can see through such lies.Getting back to ZDT the film has an absolute air of authenticity in the manner that the film is put together;through it's realistic cinematography and the fact-like manner that the script is written.Jessica Chastain is the child of post-9/11 and it has become her sole obsession in finding Bin Laden. Her performance is the heart and soul of the film and the perfect actress for audiences to relate with and go on this disturbing journey of suicide bombers, IED bombers and fanatic terrorists who would not stop at nothing to see the deaths of Americans and innocent civilians.As for conspiracy theorists one might say why Bin Laden did not have underground tunnels to make a quick getaway? Since no one has seen his body or any photo's for that matter ( photo's in todays digital age can be easily manipulated and have little credibility)sceptics would say it was a propaganda ploy for the USA and West to move onto other parts of the world and give people their catharsis in the death of Bin Laden.As for the film ZDT from a filmmaking aspect should have won best picture then ARGO. ARGO is a feel good movie and sat well with the Academy. ZDT and THE HURT LOCKER at this point are some of the best films dealing with terrorism alongside Steven Spielbergs MUNICH and the '60's film THE BATTLE OF ALGIERS. How truthful ZDT is I don't know. A lot of questions have been left unanswered since the Bush family had been involved in buisness dealings with the Bin Laden family. Only time will tell and maybe 20 years from now when sensitivity has died down to a certain extent we might get a film similar to Oliver Stones JFK.
summary: How close to the truth is?

reviewText: I knew the outline of the plot (doesn't everybody?) going in, yet the movie was as interesting and dramatic as I have seen.  The actress playing the CIA agent holds the entire movie together and does a superb job.  The fact that a woman is the central protagonist in a violent movie, makes for interesting takes on the drama and feminism -  there's no off-duty whooping-up, letting off steam, at most there's a dinner with colleagues (which ends in an explosion), the scene at the end where the pilot asks `where are you headed', I presume was meant to be a question about the USA, but I came away thinking `will she be able to settle down and have a family' (sorry).There has been a lot of comment about the torture scenes, I think the film is pretty clear that the intelligence picture of Bin Laden's associates was gained by torture, and that the torture itself involved physical and psychological elements.  It looked pretty brutal to me, though its impact on the torturers seemed underplayed - surely it depraves both the victim and the inflictors?  If anything the torture sessions seemed to have been tamer versions of reality - there are some similar, though more graphic descriptions from a recent book by Stuart Couch called The Terror Courts: Rough Justice at Guantanamo Bay.I thoughts some parts of the script were a bit weak - why does the central character have to swear when she is at her first meeting with the CIA director and others after having found the safe house?  Is it really credible that the CIA would have to bribe a Kuwaiti with a sportscar, to get a telephone number?  On this one, I presumed it was too crazy not to have been true.Why does the CIA director find her in the canteen and ask her what else she has done for the CIA? When she replies `nothing', he says `you are very good at that'.  What is this about?  Is he trying to undermine her analysis ?.  It seems like a worms-eye view.  I can't see Leon Panetta doing that.  Still it was good to see Tony Soprano again, though I'm worried about his weight.These, however, are just quibbles.  The movie was excellent, the pace was terrific, the plot was very tense, the main character (on the whole) was very credible.  I would watch this again.I left the cinema thinking that we know this story so well, and its so controversial that I wouldn't be surprised if its an elaborate hoax, that Bin Laden might have been betrayed by some members of Saudi Intelligence or his extended family (a number of his wives were in the house) and that this is a cover story which protects them from retaliation.  But that's real-world stuff, the movie is excellent either way.

reviewText: Kathryn Bigelow should never make another movie again. She is awful. It's sad that she is so well-connected in Hollywood enough to get nominated for garbage that she directs. Zero Dark Thirty was an awful movie. First of all, it was boring. I was psyched to watch this movie. I like war movies, and I felt that this couldn't miss. It's all about finding Osama. How can you screw that up? I was wrong. This film was self-indulgent. There was no flow to the story line. It's a bunch of mundane scenes, one after the other, with a very bored, uncharacteristically mediocre performance from Jessica Chastain. Her character, Maya, strikes you as a very disturbed individual. She appears to have never even taken a class on Middle Eastern Studies in college. The portrayal of her character is very one-dimensional, and she comes off as a very strange individual. Her motivation to catch Osama is never genuine. She comes off as being brainwashed. You would think someone that works for the CIA would be depicted as a bit more educated and aware of the political issues in the Middle East. Nope, she's a self-indulgent, narcissistic drone. I mean, if this truly was reality, make the character more sympathetic to audiences!!! The way she was depicted turns the audience against her, hard to imagine, as an American myself.Many had issue with the torture scenes. Yes, it was strange. Was it pro-torture? Who knows. Was it awkward? Very. Just not well-integrated into the film.The final raid, well, I truly hope that was not accurate. It was like watching storm troopers in action, killing anything that moved. If this truly did happen, Bigelow should have Hollywoodized it, because it just did not look good, especially the scene in which the unarmed wife came to the aid of her fallen husband and was shot. Wow. Several more unarmed men were shot in the raid, almost like they were hunted. I understand, this was a military mission, but much of it just looked bad on film. It makes American soldiers look like monsters. Was this the intention? From what I read of the operation, there were justified reasons for their actions, but in the film, it looked like something else.On its own merits, this was just a bad movie. It was probably rushed to get the film out to theaters instead of doing a proper job. Furthermore, Kathryn Bigelow is a mediocre director, confirmed. She stinks. She has no talent whatsoever when it comes to making movies. Oh, she's been nominated for Oscars and won? Who cares, the show has no credibility anymore. The Academy routinely ignores excellent action movies and actors. Gary Oldman, anyone? Hillary Swank, Halle Berry, Jennifer Lawrence, Adrien Brody, Jeff Bridges, Sean Penn, Jennifer Hudson, Jaime Foxx, even Nicholas Cage, have won Oscars while he has been snubbed repeatedly. That's a joke. I believe more than a few of those actors are either B-list, or damn near close to it. Lawrence will be B-list soon, mark my words.Don't be fooled. Don't even watch this movie for free. It's boring, it's disgusting, and it's bad. I will never watch another Kathryn Bigelow movie again. I'm not crazy. She is just a terrible, overrated director.

reviewText: With time the film has become a lot less pungent and pregnant than it was when it came out. It is nothing but a fiction documentary on an essential event of the beginning of the 21st century. There was September 11, 2001 before and now there is May 2, 2011. The ten years during which terrorism seemed to be dominating the world and the USA to be running after an uncatchable ghost, will remain the ten years during which the West ran after its own tail like a deranged dog.And Osama Ben laden was a ghost. He had managed to be ever present everywhere and to be untraceable at all in any way imaginable. No telephone link. No Internet connection; No going out of his fortress at all. A fortress well hidden right in the middle of an urban area in Pakistan, 585 feet or so from the main Pakistani military academy, their West Point. To be unseen hide in a crowd. To be invisible hide in a fortress that stands out on its surrounding neighborhood and protect it in the most standard way so that everyone may think it is the residence of a drug lord. And it would have worked if there had not been one girl who was crazy enough to believe what her reason and deduction told her with certainty though she had no material proof of the presence of her target.She was a subductive mind who built a conviction from a pile of circumstantial and partial facts and subductive she had to be to subdue all the males around her in the secret service, CIA, armed forces and other agencies of the type, subdue indeed, if not abduct their rational mind for a trip onto the other side of visible reality, the invisible side of reality. To believe is at times enough.But the film was a very scandalous film when it came out because of the torture used to get some information. The case was abducted out of reasonable behavior and intelligence. First the only TV skimpy appearance of Obama was when he declared he would put an end to torture. All the torture took place in the film before that declaration. That's an ellipse, my dear film viewers, meaning that Obama put a stop to torture. Then the film even shows how a "tip" was in fact a trap that led a loaded car into a military base in Afghanistan and it exploded killing many, including some CIA agents who were so happy to have invited someone in the base who was going to tell them where Ben Laden was and all that with the torture of greed, for 25 million dollars. Idiotic. Money is a very good bait for suicide bombers.So torture did not give them a lot. And money did not give them a lot. It is only crossing and crisscrossing intelligence from many sources that led to a track, a trail, a path to the man they were looking for. Nothing replaces intelligence, and I should say a vast diversity of intelligence. Nothing is better than human intelligence, I mean intellectual work, to build a conviction from a mass of data that seems to have no logic at all. No machine could reach that conviction because a machine would work on probabilities, and let me say subduction, the truth emerging from the deeper layers of the accumulated data, is irrational, illogical, absurd in many ways. That's how Homo Sapiens invented God. Today we use it in science all the time.As for the unethical side of torture, it is a very bad argument. Of course it is unethical but Guantanamo will only close when the last prisoner there dies provided they don't bring any anymore. Guantanamo nevertheless worked and works very well because of the reputation it has, the myth about it and the legend about the methods used there. Of course it is unethical but with terrorists fear is the best incentive to try anything to defy that fear, to defy reason and prudence and to get caught.Torture is ineffective as for the intelligence it brings out but it is unluckily effective in the fear it creates in some people on the wrong side of the divide of humaneness because then they get reckless, sloppy, careless and even talkative. In fact real torture is not necessary. Just a public reputation about it is enough to reach its target. And yet real torture in inhuman and unethical.But once again the manhunt of the first decade of the 21st century was constructed on real intelligence obtained through intelligent collecting and not fake intelligence obtained through torture. Was torture actually used or not? Who knows really. We can trust the perversion of some intelligence gatherers for them to turn themselves into torture-masters. But these are probably the little ones on the chain, particularly if we are speaking of physical torture. And it takes a woman to know that a woman witness to a torturing session is a lot more effective on the man who is being tortured than the torture itself because the presence of a woman becomes psychological torture that is untenable for real Islamic people from the Arab or Middle-East world. To be stripped naked in front of a woman is the worst psychological and moral torture you can invent in that situation.Christians on the other hand are used to the quasi-naked Christ tortured to death on his cross and Jesus did not wince at the presence of his own mother and Mary Magdalena at the foot of the cross, and a third Mary, at least in the conscience of Christians who even believe Jesus presented John as being her son now, directly from the cross.Torture is not what you may think it is. I am just surprised this film essentially shows physical torture and body pain caused by violence. I am sure the locking up of one torture victim in a box was a lot more effective though it was not hurting the body at all. But the mind...!!!This film has to be seen and known as a fiction documentary on an important event of our time.Dr Jacques COULARTDEAU

reviewText: This is one of the great movies of all time for some of the same reasons that LINCOLN received so much acclaim.  Nevertheless, dirty deal-making and bribery that were employed to pass the 13th Amendment in a severely divided House in 1865 must seem relatively tame compared to the depiction of nauseating and disgraceful acts of torture and humiliation inflicted on prisoners in efforts to extact information concerning the location of Bin Laden.  This movie is unappologetic in its quest for realism and detail.  However disturbing it is -- and it really is disturbing in many ways -- the search for Bin Laden and for some measure of justice or closure following the dreadful crimes of 911 is as much a part of the history of our own time as was the final, legal destruction of Slavery in 1865 for those who suffered through the Civil War.The acting was first rate as was the depiction of the assault on Bin Laden's compound.  While Maya and the leading specialists in the operation were given prime focus in this movie, it is also clear that the effort required the skill and intensely hard work by many individuals as well as a good measure of luck. One can empathize with the frantic and seemingly unhinged Maya as she scrawls numbers on the office wall of her CIA boss  ---  29, 51, 100, 129 etc. --- depicting the number of days after she unveiled the location of what she is utterly convinced is the hiding place of Osama Bin Laden before action was finally taken.You will want to buy the dvd and re-watch certain sequences as the complex and difficult process may not be easy to absorb in one viewing.

reviewText: It's hard for most of the current world to think about the major events that took place during the course of their lives without thinking about September 11th, 2001. It was a day that marked a turning point for the whole world and the way they thought about their enemies. There was no declaration of war; there was no indication that there would be an attack, and perhaps most importantly, there was no one specific country that the world could point to say, "This is our enemy". This is part of what Kathryn Bigelow's ZERO DARK THIRTY is all about; it's about a quest of epic proportions to find the one man the world knows is responsible for that horrific attack, but it's a man who is hidden from the world with no real country to call his own and a seemingly endless hidden network that could and did strike at any time all over the world.This quest is given a human face in the personage of Maya (Jessica Chastain), a CIA case officer who has been working on one assignment since her beginnings at the Agency: Finding and killing Usama Bin Laden. Her quest begins in 2003 in the Middle East at one of the CIA's many "black sites", a series of undisclosed locations where terror suspects are held in secret for interrogation. The chief officer for many of the interrogations is Dan (Jason Clarke), a man whose scruffy exterior belies a cool, centered intelligence and a man who finds himself with the very unpleasant job of applying whatever pressure is necessary to get the information he needs. Throughout the first act of the film, there are incredibly unsettling scenes of what the Administration of the time so successfully rebranded as "enhanced interrogation", but some bits and pieces of information begin to form a pattern for Maya which brings us into the second act of the film, which is largely the pursuit of these leads and pulling on each possible thread until it comes undone to reveal the last pieces of the puzzle. The third act then gives us the fateful day that the authorization came down to utilize Seal Team Six to assault the compound in Pakistan that UBL had been hiding in.It is an incredibly hard thing to craft a suspenseful and non-melodramatic film around one of the most important moments of the last few years, and make it an incredibly tense, vital, and unromanticized film, but Bigelow and writer Mark Boal (the same team that gave us THE HURT LOCKER, the deserving winner of Best Picture at the 2009 Academy Awards) give us a film that throws the audience and its protagonists all around the world as the pursuit intensifies, then seems to fall apart, but then picks right back up. As the film opens, we see that this film is based on "first-hand" accounts of the incidents portrayed within, and you get the feeling right from the outset that what you're seeing on-screen not just looks, but feels totally authentic.Behind the camera, Bigelow gives again a very documentarian approach that worked so incredibly well in THE HURT LOCKER and also works well telling the story of Maya, and only really shifting points of view when major events take place. It never strays away from her story, but it allows the other key players on the board to give testimony of sorts of the jobs they're doing, whether it's awaiting the arrival of a key informant, to the tracking of one cell phone in a crowded marketplace, to the assault on the compound itself. The camera movement is jerky at times, but only in service of the story its telling. The rhythm of the editing by William Goldenberg and Dylan Tichenor works in total concert with the visual story that Bigelow is telling. Boal's writing is crisp, sharp and smart with a real ear for dialogue and interaction.This is a much more sprawling tale than THE HURT LOCKER as we get numerous characters in a number of different duties, and a who's-who of terrific character actors in these many roles: Jennifer Ehle (CONTAGION, THE KING'S SPEECH) as fellow case worker Jessica, Kyle Chandler (the TV FRIDAY NIGHT LIGHTS) as a section chief, Mark Strong (SHERLOCK HOLMES, TINKER TAILOR SOLDIER SPY) as one of Maya's superiors, Edgar Ramirez (the TV Mini-Series CARLOS) as an on-the-ground CIA operative, James Gandolfini as the director of the CIA, Stephen Dillane (SPY GAME, GAME OF THRONES) as the National Security Advisor, Joel Edgerton (WARRIOR) as ST6's lead, and even Harold Perrineau Jr. (LOST, THE MATRIX RELOADED), Mark Duplass (SAFETY NOT GUARANTEED) and John Barrowman (TORCHWOOD) in small but important roles. When all is said and done, however, the film is owned by Jessica Chastain. Her portrayal of Maya as someone who is confident and assured of her abilites and her intelligence, but often seems to be made to feel out of place in a political and covert world of powerful men. Her mostly unshaken faith in her mission, the intelligence she's received by hook and by crook, and the personal losses she's suffered at the hands of Al-Qaeda, is what drives her to an obsessive need to complete the mission. One of Chastain's strengths as an actress is that she's able to say so much by saying so little. This is a role of disappearence; while she may sport her beautiful firey red hair, she's unrecognizable and unconnectable to any of her previous work. It's a very non-showy performance and is the main reason that it works so incredibly well. Boal could have added more dramatic embellishments to her character by giving her more of a life outside the walls of the intelligence community that fall into the standard dramatic traps (Is she obsessed because she lost someone in 9/11? What's her home life like? Does she have a high-functioning autism? Does she fall for one of her co-workers? The list goes on and on), but thankfully, very little about her is revealed. We only learn about her through her words and deeds, and it's an astonishing performance. I remember predicting after her work on THE TREE OF LIFE that she was a woman who would have an Oscar before the decade was out, and it seems like it's going to come a lot sooner. Her final moment is absolutely devastating without being showy.The film is long, and it has a lot of information to digest. One major criticism I've seen of this film time and again is how "boring" it is and for the life of me, I can't understand that point of view. This is not your standard "manhunt" film. There is no ticking clock; there's no ace operative who takes it all down single-handedly; there's no ham-fisted attempt to amplify the natural drama of the material by dumbing it down to fit with a more conventional thriller. But even without those traditional Hollywood flourishes, this is an incredibly exciting and tension-packed film because despite knowing what's coming, unless you have times and dates committed to memory, you never really know what's going to happen. But even if you might find the first two acts dull, you cannot deny the final act of the assault on the compound which is, for all intents and purposes, a blow-by-blow recreation of that night, and it's stunning, heart-stopping, and brilliantly staged.ZERO DARK THIRTY is not the end-zone dance that so many expected from a political point of view, and from a cinematic point of view, it might not be as well-rounded as THE HURT LOCKER, but this is an important, vital and exceptionally well-made film that deserves to be at the top of accolades for 2012's year in film.
summary: A Cinematic Powerhouse, and Another Triumpth for Bigelow and Boal.

reviewText: After this movie and The Hurt Locker, I'm having a hard time getting my mind wrapped around why Bigelow gets under my skin (that's a compliment) with her no-nonsense approach.  My best guess is that it's her use of restraint.She's documentary-style, but restrains herself from shaking the crap out of the camera.  She shows violence matter-of-factly, sometimes in-your-face, but restrains herself from sensationalizing it.  She builds suspense, but she doesn't compromise a certain calmness and naturalness to do so.  Her sparse use of music (less sparse here than in Hurt Locker, but still the opposite end of the spectrum from, say, The Dark Knight Rises' bombastic score) and emotion are effective, too.  In short, there are tons of quiet choices that impress me, places where I so expected her to milk something for all it was worth but she never did.  And yet she didn't use quiet in that super-jarring way that keeps any rhythm from forming.  You see, it's really hard for me to figure out what she's doing that I like so much, but this has been as close as I've gotten.I think maybe she's borrowed (another compliment) some style points from Soderbergh, but definitely has her own voice. I'm really glad she's making films.  I don't think she's an absolute master yet (as in top 25 director of all time), but boy did she come close with this one.  I think her film beat Argo all to hell, and I'm a big fan of Ben Affleck's directing, too.I did think there was a spot in the middle where my concentration was tested by the pacing, but I can't give it less than 5 stars just because the strong parts were so very strong.  If great film-making were more common, maybe I could dock it a little, but it isn't.
summary: Is It Restraint That Makes Bigelow So Good?

reviewText: About halfway through the filming of her military thriller about the CIA's hunt for terrorists, Academy Award winning Director Kathryn Bigelow ("The Hurt Locker") was stunned to learn that Osama bin Laden had been captured and killed. She immediately suspended her project and Mark Boal ("The Hurt Locker") began rewriting the script.Amid accusations that she (possibly) was given access to secret material, she shot and released this astonishing piece of R-rated film-making with blinding speed. Of course we already know how it ends, but it's a nail-biter just the same. And it IS based on real people; they even remembered to include the Malinois dog (a slightly smaller version of a German Shepherd).We see:* Jessica Chastain ("The Help") is the driven CIA agent who refuses to cut herself or anyone else any slack. She got this job right out of high school and it's the only life she knows. (You should hear how she describes herself!)* Mark Strong ("The Guard") practically steals this film from the top-billed stars. This British-born actor never ceases to amaze me: this time he's CIA (American!) and grabs our focus any time he's on camera.* Jason Clarke ("Lawless") is the CIA fellow tasked with the interrogation of prisoners. This Australian bloke will always work because he speaks American like a native.* Joel Edgerton ("Kinky Boots") is part of the Navy SEAL team and he believes in our heroine's "gut." Edgerton is another Aussie.* Chris Pratt ("Money Ball") brings his trademark genial likability to his role as part of the SEAL team. So much of their raid has them swathed in night-vision goggles and all the paraphernalia they need that they are virtually unrecognizable, but I knew his voice.* Reda Kateb ("Three Worlds") is the operative who is subjected to water-boarding. The scene wasn't as horrific as I had feared, although I certainly wouldn't want it done to ME!* Kyle Chandler ("Super 8") is our heroine's boss in Afghanistan. To him, she is a major pain because she doesn't know how to quit.* Jennifer Ehle ("Contagion") is her only friend in the CIA. As a rule, Ms. Ehle speaks flawless American but one scene shocked me because there was NO attempt to disguise her British pronunciation. Hmmm.... Oh well, this was made in a rush...It's amazing how iconic a simple, three-story white building in Abbottabad, Pakistan has become. We all recognize it instantly! And the claustrophobic scenes inside are grim. Expect bits of humor, no sweaty bodies, plenty of gunfire and (remember we are dealing with suicide bombers!) lots of blowie uppie stuff.Amazon will notify me when it's available to order.

reviewText: ZDT is a director Kathryn Bigelow's brilliant telling of the hunt for Osama bin Laden, starting in the sand-blown huts of various CIA dark sites and culminating in the raid on UBL's compound in Abbottabad, Pakistan. Little is held back - depictions of torture and brutality, even the infamous practice of waterboarding - in the hunt for information about UBL's whereabouts. The section of the film that details the operation by Seal Team Six is riveting. Shot alternatively in near darkness and via night-vision goggles worn by the troops, the operation is shown second by second, with its missteps (killing the unarmed wife of a resident, the crash of one of the copters) and successes (killing bin Laden, ransacking his computers and files). But while the film depicts America's greatest success in the War on Terror, its mood is subdued -- not quite celebratory.The film's main character, Maya, a fictional female CIA agent played by Jessica Chastain (and who may represent a single person or the hundreds of analysts and agents who worked on the hunt) is a bit of a cipher. She is slight and freckled, is called a "killer," and is inexplicably drawn to take down the Al Qaeda leader. Maya is hardened, or pretends to be, and unfazed by violence. But in spite of representing the desire of the American public for UBL's scalp, she's kind of hard to root for. She is taciturn, cold and driven by unknown motives. She unflinchingly watches a man beaten to provide evidence, then coolly tells him that the severity of his treatment is in his own hands. She has no backstory, though it would be easy (if clichéd) to give her one - say, that her Dad died in the Twin Towers or on Flight 93. But though the film begins with a series of desperate phone calls from 9/11, that attack seems almost beside the point to Maya -- as though her desire to take down UBL has taken on a life of its own, apart from any connection to the assault on the homeland.There are strange inklings throughout the movie that we are watching the intersection of physical reality and its underlying shadow of meaning, For instance, the search for bin Laden's courier and the raid on Abbottabad are told realistically and in detail. But the moment of UBL's death is curiously concealed, and is just-so-slightly inconsistent with written accounts. (Caution: spoilers ahead!) Two SEALS creep toward Osama's 3rd floor hideout via a narrow stairway. They hear a noise and shoot through a curtained door. When they enter, UBL is on his back, dead or nearly so, with two of his wives screaming nearby. The SEALs pump two more rounds into bin Laden to ensure his demise. An AK-47 is seen in the room, but mounted on the wall above UBL's bed, not even within arm's reach. Viewers who might want to see him die a slow and painful death - face to face with his lethal visitors, perhaps, or menacing them with an automatic weapon -- will be disappointed. His death seems anti-climactic- intricately planned and executed, to be sure -- but hardly the cinematic climax that such films promise. Does Bigelow show us what really happened? Is there a message in this her restraint at the moment of triumph? Or is she exercising poetic license to make a point? If so, what point? That exterminating this world-menacing terrorist leader was the equivalent of killing a fly with a sledgehammer?  Osama bin Laden, the most-wanted terrorist kingpin, murderer of thousands, ends up being an unarmed medieval in a robe and turban, hiding with his wives and kids in a ramshackle concrete "fortress," tracked down over 10 years and the cost of how much treasure, and eliminated by the world's most disciplined, armed and technically advanced armed force of all time. If Kathryn Bigelow is trying to say something here, I can only wonder what it is.For all its realism, great writing and fine acting, ZDT is hard to applaud whole-heartedly. Maybe we have just become nuanced about our place in the world. Openly hating a militant Muslim and cheering his death is perilously close to hating everyday Muslims - our workmates and neighbors. Better not to go there. Then there's the whole speculative depiction of Operation Neptune Spear, the raid on UBL's hideout. Given the secrecy of the raid, and the reluctance of most of the participants to talk about it, we aren't completely sure what happened. We do know that Bigelow made some possibly unhistorical choices. The depictions of UBL's nasty head wound are cleaned up here. Who knows what else was doctored to make the raid more palatable? Another issue with cheering for the film is the violence and self-propelling viciousness that we are asked to accept as the means for bringing bin Laden to justice. I am not nave enough to think war and espionage are pretty. But I was unable to walk away from ZDT without a few thought about the morality of torture and "extraordinary rendition," that sanitized term for sending suspects to countries where physical and mental abuse of prisoners is accepted.At the end of the film, Maya is bundled, alone, into a cargo plane. Asked where she'd like to go, she does not answer. Instead, she weeps softly. This scene brings her character closest to that of Americans reacting to the death of their number one enemy. Which is: not much at all. Whether due to war weariness or lack of confirming video, most of us did not rush into the streets when we heard the news. A decade of searching had turned UBL into a dangerous, but fairly contained evil - a devil in a glass jar. His death had little influence on those who took to heart his call for jihad against the West. As the recent Boston Marathon bombings show us, the enemies of the West do not need a living UBL to inspire them. Self-radicalization may be bin Laden's toxic legacy to the world.Why Maya's tears? Were they tears of relief at the end of a grueling, years-long effort to rid the world of an evildoer? Were they delayed tears of grief over friends who died trying to bring UBL to justice? Were they tears of lost innocence, mourning for a perhaps nonexistent time when Americans didn't torture and were not put in a position where they had to? Did the death of bin Laden, the man whose death had overtaken her entire career, leave her with a sense of lost purpose? Or did she see the death of Osama bin Laden, after so much effort and expenditure,  as insignificant in relation to her expectations? We don't know.This ambiguity - not the detailed reconstruction of bin Laden's hideout or the tactics of Seal Team 6 -- may be the film's greatest achievement, depicting events hyper-realistically, while allowing their multifaceted sorrows and joys play out in the viewer's mind long after the closing credits.

reviewText: In "Zero Dark Thirty," CIA agent Maya represents and channels the American subconscious desire to find and kill Osama bin Laden once and for all.  We know very little about Maya -- where she is from, what motivated her to join the CIA, and what her motivations are for doing anything really -- and what we do know does not form  a multi-dimensional character:  Maya is obsessed with finding and killing Osama bin Laden, and she's convinced she has to fight the world to get to him.  Early on in the manhunt she stumbles upon the name of bin Laden's courier, and without any proof or substantive evidence she thinks that this courier is the key to finding bin Laden.  She is ultimately vindicated, but in the process everyone around her thinks she's merely chasing a ghost and bending reality to suit her prejudice.Bigelow is a very subtle and courageous director.  She's not afraid of raising tough moral questions, and she's not afraid of testing the psychological and emotional limits of her audience.  The movie is intensely claustrophobic -- everything happens in small spaces -- so that when we are given wide angle shots we have to breathe with relief.  I suppose that close angle shots in tight narrow spaces is a hallmark of Bigelow's cinematography, but it also offers us an interior into Maya's mind -- as she must seclude herself away in Pakistan, away from friends and emotions.  There's not much violence in "Zero Dark Thirty," as the movie is mainly just talk and innuendo, but when it does happen it happens with great shock and effect:  the torturing of a detainee, terrorist bombings, the bullets that kill the three men in bin Laden's compound.  But the ultimate violence is inflicted by Maya on herself, as she drives herself and all those around her insane with her obsession.  The obsession becomes so integral to her identity that when she is able to stare the dead bin Laden in the face she doesn't know how to feel, and when she boards a plane by herself she doesn't know where to go, and breaks down in tears.  It's very clear from Bigelow's long close-up that these are not tears of joy -- these are real tears, tears that she had to bottle up all these years as her obsession consumed her.Like Maya herself, Bigelow is very meticulous and detail-oriented.  "Zero Dark Thirty" is a very slow, nuanced film that most viewers will find boring and aloof.  But I think that "Zero Dark Thirty's" focus on telling the story as realistically as possible is its greatest strength.

reviewText: I caught this film at the end of it's theatrical run, and was glad to have seen it on the big screen. This was a gritty, realistic take on the slow, painful slog that led to the takedown of Bin Laden in Pakistan. It has a dark, forbidding atmosphere that moves slowly and painfully toward the final raid. Kathryn Bigelow has created a darkly realistic movie that looks and feels like a documentary. Unlike Argo, which is a fast paced thriller, ZDT moves slowly until the last half hour, as CIA Analyst Maya slogs through years of lost leads and bureaucratic infighting, all the while compiling bits and pieces of evidence that finally lead to Bin Laden, and the raid at the end of the film. The Navy Seal team is well portrayed, and we see their professionalism and courage as they drop in by chopper and race to get to Bin Laden before time runs out. By the time of the raid, we have almost forgotten that the success of the raid is a forgone conclusion. The final scene is riveting, realistic, and satisfying. Don't let the torture scenes deter you; they are disturbing but not gruesome, if that makes sense. There is a brooding moodiness and tension here that carry you right into the film. In any case, don't miss it!

reviewText: Okay, I'm gonna get slammed for honking my own horn here, but it seems like I just wrote a book about something along these lines a few months ago. The first time I caught this one, it was at the fifteen-minute mark. The second time was from the beginning, and it was hard to believe I was watching a docudrama. Then again, I did know all about Abu Ghraib and Guantanamo, but wasn't Barack Osama claiming he was closing all that stuff down? Of course, Obama Bin Laden does warrant an exception...but that may be what The Standard and Zero Dark Thirty have in common.The flick itself is a quality piece of work. Maya (Jessica Chastain) is a CIA agent reluctantly transferred to the Middle East after 9/11, and she is paired with expert CIA torturer Dan (Jason Clarke) to find out who knocked our lights out at the WTC. It doesn't take long for Dan to get burnt out on the job, but Maya starts following some quality leads and soon gets a laser focus on Bin Laden himself. Despite frustrating nay-saying and spineless vacillation from CIA chief Joseph Bradley (Kyle Chandler), she finally runs the ball straight to the White House where Bin Laden's namesake gives the Navy SEALs the go-ahead to plant Global Enemy Number One six feet under. You got to give Chandler a lot of credit here. Nailing both King Kong and UBL onscreen in the same decade is no mean feat.I suppose the soliloquy here would be about how much is too much as far as human rights goes. In The Standard, you've got Jack Gawain hacking baddies to pieces to get information in foiling a mini-nuke terrorist strike in the USA. In Zero Dark Thirty, Dan restricts himself to near-drowning the perps, ninety-six hours of sleep deprivation, and shoving them in cubicles slightly bigger than a breadbox. I mean, don't we have some kind of drugs that get these jobs done? We're all aware that sodium pentatol doesn't work well on super-geniuses like Hannibal Lecter, but that flick's almost two decades old. Street dealers have improved their products by quantum leaps in comparison. Plus we question making an exception for baddies, UBL or not. Now the Psycho Sheik's gone, who do make the next exception for? The top guy in Iraq, Afghanistan, Pakistan or Mexico? When will it be okay for us to zap the top drug dealer here in KC? A few healthy doses of electroshock can save a lot of lives, y'know...well, you get the picture.Speaking of getting the picture, Zero Dark Thirty joins Argo and Life of Pi as three of the best picks of the year. Like Jarhead and The Hurt Locker, they won't be the kind of flick you'll watch a dozen times, but they sure as heck are worth the Amazon price for a popcorn Saturday night.

reviewText: Zero Dark thirty dramatizes the United States operation that found and killed Osama bin Laden. Like most movie adaptations of real events, it sometimes strays from the historic version to provide an entertaining movie going experience.  That doesn't mean that it is a bad movie, it is a very entertaining, dramatic and suspenseful even though you know how it ends.  Jessica Chastain does a great job at playing the hard as nails driven to obsession CIA agent who tracked down Bin Laden.  Although there are some controversial scenes such as the torture and waterboarding of individuals, it does not detract from the movie being a well told, well acted entertaining film.  I think the film does a nice job at giving you some things to think about, such as whether torture is a means to an ends when it comes to terrorism without being too political on the message.  It rightly portrays the real heroes of the movie, the men who risked their lives to go after Bin Laden and the people who worked on the intel for years to find him.  And even if the events aren't always true to life, it does a great job at making it believable and worth watching.
summary: Good dramatized version of the events

reviewText: I haven't watched any movies about 9/11 or it's aftermath because it was our Pearl Harbor and I couldn't watch those movies probably for the same reason that the survivors of Pearl Harbor couldn't talk about it. We're all survivors of 9/11 because we all witnessed it and felt its impact in real time. "Zero Dark Thirty" gives you some of that real time immediacy in the assassination of Osama Bin-Laden."Zero Dark Thirty" starts where the hunt for Bin-Laden did with 9/11, almost. There's a black screen while we hear the final 911 phone calls of those killed, and our mind fills in the images. The movie then follows CIA operative Maya (Jessica Chastain) as she goes on a decade long quest to find Osama Bin-Laden. She utilizes water-boarding, she loses friends to bombings, and finally tracks down Bin-Laden's whereabouts by tracking Bin-Laden's courier. Director Kathryn Bieglow ("The Hurt Locker", and "Point Break") utilized government resources that were available, but like any movie that is "based on a true story" you have to realize that some real life characters will be condensed into one character, chronologies will be juggled for more dramatic impact, and artistic license will create scenes that may not have really happened. Despite all that, Bieglow's "Zero Dark Thirty" breaks through the fog of war, undeclared as it was and more of an exercise in intelligence than active war, and shows the true nature of war that is ugly and reveals truths about the inhumanity we can inflict upon each other. Any movie that tells the truth about war is inherently an anti-war movie.When the Navy Seal team moves through the building that Bin-Laden is hiding in during their effort to kill him, the movie makes no real bones about that being the objective, just as it probably was in real life. As the Seals move from floor to floor it has a weird resonance back to Bruce Lee's last movie "The Game of Death" where each level of the building is more and more difficult and brings a greater danger. The resolution of the movie isn't very satisfying even though we know Bin-laden was killed, but the Seal team isn't sure until Maya confirms it. There's no jingoistic, flag waving ending which there could have been. The movie started with the sounds of 9/11, it could have ended with footage of people running to the White House celebrating the announcement of Bin-Laden's death. Instead, the movie shows Maya alone, without a goal in life as her raison d'etre for living for the past decade is now gone.
summary: Zero Dark Thirty Cuts Through Fog of War to Reveal its Truths

reviewText: Being honest, I thought that since it came out of Hollywood, it would be another mouthpiece for politicians in Washington (ALL of them, OK?). I am one of those weirdos who want what is best for our wonderful country, not what is best for some selfish, greedy politician. So, with that out of the way, this movie was spectacular, both in it's photographic perfection, and in the story it told.And what a story it was. Who knew that OBL was such a crying coward? Kathryn Bigalow did an amazing job of not only ferreting out the real story, but also showed real courage in not pandering to whatever politician brought this bad man to his necessary end. If you are on either the far left or right of the middle politically, you might not find this story satisfying simply because she did NOT give in and make it political.Perhaps, for me, the most astonishing part was finding out that a single woman in her stubborn search for the truth and in finding this vermin, finally made him pay for the thousands of innocent people he murdered. It was a very tense movie, reminiscent of Homeland in which I understand the beautiful character of Carrie in Homeland is based. Nobody in their right minds wants to see violence just for the sake of violence. But I have to say, watching this movie span 12+ years as our country underwent changes in Washington politics and the effect it had on the "war" on terrorism was almost as spell-binding as the search for OBL which is the main premise of this movie. Jessica Chastain as that woman put in an Oscar-worthy performance which unfortunately, didn't happen, brought her to life in a similar way that Clare Danes in Homeland does and got the Emmy for it!Well done, Ms. Bigelow. Far better than I expected it to be. Highly recommended for most people. A true lesson for the history books.
summary: A Story That Needed To Be Told

reviewText: To the men and women who made this movie: Thank you for telling us absolutely nothing useful about the so-called "War on Terror." Everything covered in this movie was already told - and told better - by newspapers, the Internet and news TV/radio stations. What this movie did, however, is just copy and paste the same stories and presented them in a 2  hour format, with very little background story or character development. By omitting background story and character development, this movie actually made it less believable to see and believe the movie. Not only that, but it also makes "Zero Dark" a very lazy way to a make a movie.So now that all this time, talent and money have been spent on telling us absolutely nothing, why don't they - the big Hollywood filmmakers - take time telling stories that matter?! If they want to tell stories about 9/11, why not start by asking questions. Questions such as: Who financed the attack? Who/which parties benefited from it? How was it possible to attack the most powerful nation on earth? What led the attackers to attack America? What was their reason for the attack? Did the fact that they were trained by the CIA to kill the Soviets - the infidels - and then allowed to keep their weapons and funding to attack the US have anything to do with 9/11? Why were the very drugs that funded terrorist operations allowed to grow and increase AFTER the US invaded Afghanistan? Why wasn't Bin Laden captured when the US had him surrounded in Afghanistan? Did Bin Laden even exist? Did he have help/support inside the US in the 9/11 attacks? Who were his connections and supporters? Are/Were any US politicians involved? What role did corporations play in the 9/11 attacks? Instead of invading the whole country of Iraq, why weren't the same tactics that got Bin Laden used to get Saddam Hussein? So on; so on, and so on...By contrast, "Argo" - another movie made last year about the "actual" events in the Mid-East - took time to do some research and tell a credible story. While some of the events may have changed in that movie, the movie itself was very entertaining and very well directed by Ben Affleck. "Zero Dark Thirty," however, takes itself way too seriously, but at the end delivers none of the thrills or entertainment value it's expected to deliver.Don't get me wrong here, though, I'm not suggesting that all movies should deliver entertainment and nothing more. What I'm suggesting is that if you are not presenting all the facts (as in Zero Dark's case), or are presenting them in a way that makes them seem stupid and unbelievable, then, at least, you should deliver some entertainment value, if nothing else.Having said that, I do understand that it's difficult to make an "entertaining" movie about such a difficult subject - terrorism - which any way one looks at it, presents the darkest moments in human history. Darkest moments because a group of men, either driven by religious extremism/revenge/money/whatever attacked and killed thousands of innocent people, and then another group of men - a much larger one - went after them and attacked, not caring that their attack too would end up destroying many innocent lives. It's also a very dark chapter because all the facts of both the 9/11 attacks and, of what led the attackers to attack, have been kept secret from the public.So if you loved this movie, please do consider the points I presented here before commenting on my review. My main argument is that this movie took the easy way out and just retold events as they were covered by the news media. Would I be wrong to expect that the movie had taken more time to present a story with a background as to what led to the attacks in the first place? Because I believe that when those very hard questions are asked, and then when they are researched and answered as accurately as possible, that that's when a movie or story rises above the sum of its parts. Otherwise, it's just another average movie or story. And I happen to not like average movies. Period!
summary: Tell Me Something I Don't Know!

reviewText: I don't know about calling something like this entertainment, but I did enjoy it.  It was only slightly slow in places, but it still didn't prevent me from continuing to watch it. Naturally the President said he caught Bin Laden, but obviously it wasn't him that did.  It was this actual soldier and this woman behind the scenes who went on a decade long hunt for him.Spoiler alert if you haven't seen this:The Camp Chapman attack.  The way its depicted in the movie has this CIA agent letting someone who is a threat into the facilities in hopes of interviewing him.  She can't understand why the guards are at the gate stopping him and she asks them to allow him access.  If this really did happen, I find it hard to believe that a supposedly intelligent CIA agent would allow someone who is affiliated with the Al Qaeda into the facility.  Anyone with any measure of intelligence I assumed knew that these terrorists and Al Qaeda connections will sacrifice their own lives just to murder you.  What on Earth propelled her to drop her guard?  The answer to this question is not revealed in the film for some reason.  Regardless, this was worth watching.

reviewText: ...which, historically, a lot of the best films do.For me, this film has two unusual qualities;1) Its greatest weakness is also its greatest strength. It takes pains to keep its distance, to stay neutral andunemotional. It refuses to assign easy labels, to people or issues, even (as has been much discussed) beingambiguous about the use of torture. It gives very little back-story, even of the lead character. It doesn't work to winyou to a point of view, to make you want to cheer your approval, or shake your head in shame, or even like or dislikethe characters.For most of the film I found the effect (as one might expect) oddly alienating. I was gripped by the story, but I didn'tfeel strong emotions, or care about characters in the way a 'normal' film would have made me. And while watching,this felt like a weakness. I felt distracted, disappointed, even bored at times, regardless of the dramatic nature of the story.Yet that same quality led me to feeling powerfully haunted by the film when it was over -- to ponder violence and itseffects on human beings, the thin lines between perseverance and obsession, the inability to ever have a clear moralityin time of war. By stubbornly, steadfastly refusing to spoon feed me it's own opinions,  it forced me to think, uncomfortably,messily about a lot of things, for myself.2) It's also a film where, for me, to a large degree the whole movie is redeemed by its final images,Spoiler in next line!In finally dramatizing the lost beyond words state of our lead character, suddenly all the emotionshe never allowed herself and us is paid off in seeing that hard facade crack.  We are left with the terribleemptiness of even righteous revenge and the realization that both the character (and by extensionperhaps the nation?)  are unmoored and at sea with how to deal with the world they find themselves in,and in some ways helped to create. It's an image that defines the story with a question mark, not anexclamation point.  A rare thing for a 'mainstream' film.End spoiler alertUltimately a very brave, and very un-Hollywood film in pace, style and content. This is war,and people in war stripped of easy answers and even traditional 'excitement'.There are flaws (e.g. a lot of very pretty people who look more like actors than warriors), butthese are minor compared to seeing an uncompromised and deeply challenging vision.
summary: Fascinating how this film divides viewers...

reviewText: I had high hopes for this film. After all, it was based upon one of the most dramatic events in recent history and filmed by the Academy Award winning director of "The Hurt Locker".  But it failed to deliver on its potential.  Perhaps that's because the director and screenwriter made a decision to focus on their fictional central character - a young CIA agent portrayed by Jessica Chastain - rather than upon the ten-year arc of actual events leading to the killing of Osama bin Laden.  Thus, the film became a story of the Jessica Chastain character against the CIA bureaucracy, rather than a story of the United States versus terrorism.  And frankly, Chastain's character, over-written and over-acted though she is, simply isn't very believable or very interesting.Moreover, the valiant Navy Seals who made the raid upon bin Laden's compound in Pakistan are given very, very short shrift.  They're simply an indistinguishable group of one-dimensional figures stumbling around in the murky green half-light of starlight scopes, blowing up doors and climbing stairs.In "Argo", Ben Affleck took a story we all knew, with an ending that we all knew and created a gripping, fast-paced thriller.  In "Zero Dark Thirty", Katheryn Bigelow takes a story we all knew, with an ending we all knew and created a plodding story about a central character we don't care about, with one of the most unsatisfying climactic sequences ever filmed.

reviewText: "Zero Dark Thirty" is brilliant! This is how the story goes: For a decade, an elite team of intelligence and military operatives, working in secret across the globe, devoted themselves to a single goal: to find and eliminate Osama bin Laden.The cast led by Jessica Chastain (impressive in her Oscar-nominated performance as Maya) is brilliant. The directing by Kathryn Bigelow (who also produced the film and was Oscar-nominated for her producing efforts on the film) is brilliant. The story & screenplay by Mark Boal (who also produced and was, not only, Oscar-nominated for her producing efforts, but for his screenplay, as well) is brilliant.The music by Alexandre Desplat is brilliant. The cinematography by Greig Fraser is brilliant. The film editing (Oscar-nominated) by William Goldenberg & Dylan Tichenor is brilliant. The casting by Mark Bennett, Richard Hicks & Gail Stevens is brilliant. The production design by Jeremy Hindle is brilliant. The art direction by Ben Collins & Rod McLean is brilliant. The set decoration by Lisa Chugg & Onkar Khot is brilliant. The costume design by George L. Little is brilliant. The special effects supervised by Neil Corbould & Richard Stutsman, coordinated by Blair Foord & J.D. Schwalm is brilliant. The visual effects supervised by Chris Harvey & Mike Uguccioni, coordinated by Anita Ho is brilliant. The stunts coordinated by George Cottle & Stuart Thorp is brilliant.This is a brilliant and well-made film that is intriguing and entertaining in terms of its subject matter. It is also well-crafted and well-acted. Jessica Chastain gives an interestingly impressive performance as Maya. Kathryn Bigelow & Mark Boal have done a terrific follow-up to their Oscar-winning film "The Hurt Locker". This is also one of the best films of the recently-done holiday season and of the recently-done year, as well, if not, the best film of the year. This is also the Oscar contender of 2012 (of course, nominated for Best Picture and also Sound Editing, as well, of course, recently, winning in a tie with "Skyfall" for Sound Editing) to beat, the awards consideration that it has received to date, is impressive, as well.
