reviewText: This film is essentially a revenge western along the lines of "the searchers" or "true grit". Its problem is that it is by turns, long, boring and ultimately pointless. A good portion of the film consists of repetitive scenes of torture followed by capsule terrorists attacks. The film keeps hammering on the same obvious points for what seems like hours. Unlike most revenge westerns, it has no greater point to make than to just grind out the motions of the characters.The center of the film is Maya. Having no life and being passive-aggressive does not make for an interesting character. Most of the other people in the film are reduced to ciphers. The seal team, for example, is reduced to being treated like a pick-up basketball team of dumb jocks. We don't see their prepartions. We don't see the extensive planning, rehearsals and training that are well known to have went into the mission. Rather than anything real, we are given dumb unrealistic scenes like the one when they go to "area 51" to pick up their stealth helicopters. The politicians and hierarchy of the intelligence agencies are completely absent as well. The chain of command is maya, weak boss, obnoxous boss and apparently the president. Rather than reality, we are presented with a view of the world through the eyes of an angry child.The film also has the sense of being designed by committee with an objective of not offending anyone. The film avoids controversy by often trying to stay on all sides of an issue. This is particularly true of the torture scenes which have been designed seemingly to give everyone what they want. Of course the lack of any point of view on the torture makes the sheer volume of torture presented in the film all the more pointless.As with the worst sort of propaganda, the film gets people worked up about an issue thats in the past (torture) while not saying one word about what it was replaced with. If you wanted realism, post-torture "Maya" would have been shown spending most of her time writing up death lists for the "star chamber" to approve. What replaced torture is death by drone. But "responsible" people can't talk about that. At least not in a major motion picture.The raid is the opposite of thrilling. I don't find anything particularly dramatic about POV soldiers kicking down doors and going through rooms full of women and children to ultimately shoot up a bedroom.I suppose the film will appeal to the crowd who likes ultra-detailed police procedurals. But I've never liked that sort of thing myself. Its all the worse here because its a "lone" character procedural. Maya does everything. Maya is everywhere. When the team returns from Pakistan, almost nobody is there except for Maya. They don't even give us the natural epilogue of the burial at sea of OBL.The film is around 160 minutes but it feels like four hours. After a while, you could see the terrorism scenes coming from a mile away. But after a while, anything other than repetitive torture scenes seemed like a positive.The film is badly written and badly directed. I can't say anything bad about Chastain's performance because it appears that she was given nothing to work with in terms of the script. How a film this bad was nominated for the highest awards is beyond me. There were points to be made about revenge in a film like this but the film managed to touch not one of them.

reviewText: It's hard to believe that there is a young generation out there that didn't experience 9/11 first hand. For those of us who lived through it, it doesn't seem all that long ago. So this generation can't quite grasp the importance of Osama Bin Laden's death. Still, two movies came out last year with that subject at their core. One seemed little more than a promotional piece for President Obama during an election year (going so far as to include an ill timed comment by Mitt Romney who had nothing to do with the subject matter) showing almost as much of him as the SEAL team that took Bin Laden out. The other was nominated for best picture and nearly won.ZERO DARK THIRTY was noted for taking a few dramatic liberties (such as the main character actually being a composite of several main players in what unfolded) but that doesn't detract from the story being told. Jessica Chastain stars as Maya, a young CIA agent on her first time in the Middle East as the film opens. She's there during an interrogation and sees first hand how brutal it can be. While she shies away from it she stays silent.The film moves quickly from place to place, time to time through the career of Maya. She doggedly pursues any lead that could find Bin Laden. One possible lead is a courier for messages he sends out but that falls to the wayside when he apparently is killed. It's not until later in the film that she learns he came from a family with 8 brothers and it was one of them killed not the man she was searching for.Through her career we see how things change. Her passive nature turns to a desire to catch and kill her prey. When a friend is killed in a car bombing Maya becomes even more determined. Add to that a machine gun attack on her and she won't let anyone stand in her way, not even her immediate supervisors. Maya's in your face attitude may not win her a large number of friends but it does earn her respect.No, this isn't a spoiler since we know the outcome of this story. Eventually a possible site for Bin Laden is found. When a table full of bureaucrats is asked if this is a 100% surety that Bin Laden is there they each take a turn hem hawing around with smaller percentages in mind. Only Maya has the courage to say this is as close to 100$ as they are likely to ever be.Given the go ahead the last 30 minutes or so of the film deals with the SEAL team that was sent in to capture or kill Bin Laden. While the film to this point, nearly 2 hours, dealt with what it took to find him, this 30 minutes is shown from a tactical standpoint where we see the team organize then put into action the plan to take him out in action.The thing that stands out about this film is that it seems more matter of fact than most movies made. There is no John Wayne type motivating and leading a group into the battle field. This is more what the situation was like, plain and simple. The only bad thing about that is that it plays out kind of bland.Perhaps we're all still too close to the situation than we'd like to admit. Perhaps the wounds are still too exposed. Perhaps the death of Bin Laden was too quick and sudden to accept. While the story is an important one and this film does give credit where credit was due, it's still a bit slow paced and realistic to be considered entertainment. A good movie technically yes, but for enjoyment I'm not so sure. Whether you watch this film will be determined by your outlook on the situation. Yes it is a good movie, but go in knowing what to expect.

reviewText: To the Movie's credit, it does a few things well. The Movie correctly portrays the fact that enhanced interrogation succeeds. Without enhanced interrogation, hundreds of dangerous terrorist murderers would still be free and killing innocent people.  The Movie also does a good job portraying our brave Navy Seals at work. As Seal missions go, this one was rather easy. There were only two armed men at the Bin Laden compound, and they were killed in short order. The rest was mop up of women and children.  The Movie also correctly portrays the fact that finding terrorists is a team effort, which requires the work of many people and a great deal of coordinated intelligence collection.Unfortunately, the Movie fails dismally by suggesting that a fictionalized female character, Maya, almost single-handedly located Bin Laden. This is nonsense. From the moment the first interrogator (not Maya) identified a Bin Laden courier, he was a major focus of ongoing efforts by the CIA and DIA. Moreover, the Movie provides false dialogue stating there were no intelligence assets on the ground near the Bin Laden compound. (Presumably, this was to inflate the importance of the fictionalized Maya character. Interestingly, in Sanskrit, Maya means illusion. Certainly, the inflated importance of the Maya character is illusory Hollywood entertainment.) In truth, there were local intelligence assets on the ground observing the Bin Laden compound for many months or longer. Also, a Pakistani physician risked his life to provide invaluable intelligence on the occupants of the Bin Laden compound. That physician remains in Pakistani prison, after the Obama administration exposed him while bragging about the mission. Moreover, local intelligence assets observed a large, bearded man at the compound, making the identification of Bin Laden almost certain.  With their pre-mission surveillance, these assists confirmed that Bin Laden never left the compound, making his presence on the night of the mission almost certain.The most preposterous claim of the Movie is that Bin Laden was still an effective Al Qaeda leader at the time of his death and killing him would put an end to Al Qaeda. Since, at least, 2005, Bin Laden had been rendered incommunicado and ineffective as a terror leader. Of course, history shows that, even after Bin Laden's death, Al Qaeda continues to threaten and kill Americans, including our U.S. Ambassador to Libya and citizens around the world. While Bin Laden was an important psychological target for the American public, his death did not represent a major military or counter-terrorism victory. If anything, Bin Laden's death and rebirth as a spiritual martyr has given new energy and inspiration to Al Qaeda around the world including, among other things, the Al Qaeda-inspired "Arab Spring." In conclusion, Bigelow had the talent and resources to make a great movie. Instead, she succumbed to her ideological need to create a silly female lead character and implausible script surrounding her. I wish I had gone to see "Django," instead.

reviewText: "Zero Dark Thirty" is a gripping movie that presents a fiction-informed-by-fact account of the hunt for Osama Bin Laden that concluded on 1 May 2011 with the successful raid on his safehouse in Abbottabad, Pakistan where justice finally caught up to the al-Qa'ida leader.If someone asked me, "But what's the movie like?" I'd ask him or her if they'd seen the movie "the Big Red One."  That was an excellent movie made a few decades ago that depicted what the American experience in the European Theater of World War II was like by following a fictional squad as they moved from battlefields in North Africa, Italy, France, and finally Germany itself.  After a while, you realize that the squad isn't meant to be seen as a a real one but rather symbolizes all the brave soldiers that fought for America on those battlefields.The Big Red OneIt's the same thing for "Zero Dark Thirty," except the battlefields are in Afghanistan, Pakistan, Iraq, and other locales in the War on Terror.  And instead of bright-eyed GIs, the protagonists are the CIA operatives that spearheaded the hunt for Bin Laden and made the SEAL team raid in 2011 possible.  In particular, we see the CIA's hunt unfold through the eyes of "Maya" (who is modeled somewhat on a real-life CIA analyst who I have no doubt will write her own book one of these days).  As the movie unfolds, we see how the Intelligence Community was able to locate Bin Laden, by searching for a key courier who worked directly for him and then following that man back to the strange looking compound in Abbottabad where Bin Laden had been hiding (almost in plain sight of the Pakistan authorities).The movie has drawn criticism from some like John McCain who seems to believe that his experience being tortured in Vietnam makes him an authority on what interrogation measures do and do not work and some "reviewers" here on amazon (who only get upset about torture when it is allegedly being practiced by the US...as opposed to by the Chinese, Russians, or North Koreans).  I think it is fair to say that the movie oversimplifies the issue and may make people watching it think that enhanced interrogation techniques were the only reason for the success in Abbottabad.  The truth is that there were all kinds of intelligence streams that led to the successful conclusion of the manhunt.  But arguing that the movie is pro-torture is absurd.  "Zero Dark Thirty" simply shows what happened and shows that yes, sometimes people did provide useful information under such duress. I suspect that the anti-torture crowd is so insistent that it DOESN'T WORK AND HAD NOTHING TO DO WITH GETTING BIN LADEN is because they're not comfortable with making the argument simply that it's wrong on moral grounds.I only have minor criticisms of the movie apart from that.  I found myself rather skeptical that CIA operatives would discuss highly classified matters over cell phones.  I also felt that the movie gave pretty short shrift to all the other agencies out there that took part in the manhunt and whose contributions made getting Bin Laden possible.  But by and large, those are minor flaws.  So go see this movie and ignore people who condemn it (sometimes without seeing it) AS BEING PRO-TORTURE.  They're wrong.  It's pro-facts.Here are some documentaries and a book that are well-worth viewing/reading about the issues of interrogation, terrorism, and tortureWe Can Make You Talk (History Sunday)The History Channel : The Dark Art of Interrogation , Secrets of Body Language : Learn Interrogation Techniques 2 Pack CollectionThe Battle of AlgiersThe Interrogators: Inside the Secret War Against al QaedaAn article by Bruce Hoffman in the Atlantic called "A Nasty Business" (I'd provide the link but I don't believe amazon.com would allow that).

reviewText: The memories will haunt us forever. The horrible, gut-wrenching 9-1-1 calls made by trapped victims in the World Trade Center after the planes crashed into them but before the buildings crumbled to the ground. We have forced the recollection to the back of our minds, to the fringe of our consciousness, but they are always there. For nearly all Americans, there is no memory more vivid, no moment more easily recalled, than that fateful September morning.And that is how Zero Dark Thirty, Kathryn Bigelow's gritty and straightforward account of the CIA's hunt for Osama Bin Laden, begins - with the audio of those victims' calls as they vainly waited for help as the building around them burned. The opening jars viewers, unsettling them. It also immediately establishes an emotional connection with the film to the audience .The movie then fast forwards two years, to an undisclosed CIA black site somewhere in the Middle East, where detainees are being interrogated. This is where we meet Maya (played superbly by Jessica Chastain), a new CIA agent whom Washington has deemed "a killer". At first, Maya timidly joins the enhanced interrogations, mostly watching and taking a backseat as the more grizzled, veteran agent Dan (Jason Clarke).We watch as Dan and Maya discuss strategy on how best to break the detainees and glean valuable intelligence from them. Many tactics are used. Loud metal is played in the detainee's squalid quarters all night long. Prisoners are stripped naked and walked on a leash. They are forced into a small box. Waterboarding is used as prisoners are hooded and gallons of water poured over their face. Other times detainees are rewarded with nice dinners. It is a harsh reality, one that Bigelow looks at unflinchingly, if a bit dramatically.Bit by painstaking bit, Maya and Dan slowly extract information from a variety of sources. While this goes on, the years pass. More terrorist acts occur, some depicted with news coverage from the actual events. Often, its two steps forward and one step back, as dead end leads are followed to no avail. Dan leaves his foreign post to take a desk job back in Washington. Fellow CIA agents are killed by suicide bombers. A machine gun wielding terrorist attacks Maya as she leaves her protected residential compound in Pakistan one morning for work. Maya soldiers on.Maya's work is largely unrewarding but years of determined, dogged persistence eventually pay off, leading the audience to the now infamous small white compound in Abbottabad, Pakistan where Osama Bin Laden lived in obscurity.When Maya identifies the compound where she believes Bin Laden is hiding, much ado is made of the CIA brass deciding whether or not to proceed with action. While this provides the film with tension and drama, it also painted the intelligence community as reticent, afraid to take action lest it failed in the public's eye.After spending two hours with Maya, the film leaves her behind for most of the last half hour, as the viewer follows SEAL Team Six in the raid that ended with Bin Laden's killing. This conclusion to the movie is nothing less than riveting. From the ride on the stealth helicopters to the storming of the residence, everything depicted seemed refreshingly realistic, unlike too many other Hollywood action sequences that feature superhuman stunts and horrible combat tactics. While I am sure artistic license was taken, nothing was apparently out of place.Jessica Chastain's performance as Maya is remarkable. We see her transform from an almost timorous rookie into a hard-nosed, jaded veteran agent by the end of the film. Don't expect to see where she came from or learn her back story. The movie is as focused as Maya. This approach works, however, because, as I noted earlier, the audience is already emotionally invested in the movie's outcome.Bigelow's direction and Boal's screenwriting combined to make another gem. Four years ago, they collaborated together on The Hurt Locker which won the coveted Oscar for Best Picture. That year, they probably didn't deserve it. This year, they did deserve the award but were completely snubbed at the Academy Awards. Personally, I believe Chastain, Bigelow and Boal all deserved Oscars.Taking the two movies together, however, I am glad Bigelow and Boal are making films about our involvement in the Middle East. Most movie studios refuse to touch the subject with a ten foot pole, preferring to trot out movies with tired villains and plot lines involving Communists, Nazis or ambiguous European arms dealers. How refreshing it is to view movies that are actually relevant to our times!Of course, the reason the Oscars probably ignored this film (besides an unglamorous tie in sound editing) is because of the inherent political controversies embedded in a story like this. Some are miffed the enhanced interrogation techniques (e.g. waterboarding) weren't shown with medical personnel present, as allegedly all interrogations involving such measures had. Others are upset that the techniques were shown to net positive information for the CIA.I thought the scenes involving these techniques were shown for what they were: Harsh measures that were probably necessary for the occasion. Bigelow did not seem to pass judgment on the interrogation methods either way. She did her best to show them as straightforwardly as possible and let the viewers come to their own conclusions. I believe this was the best possible approach for her to take.All in all, this is an excellent movie deserving of your thought and attention. It is not light popcorn fare, though that doesn't mean it fails to entertain. It is intimate as it traces Maya's personal story and historic and sweeping in the plot's climax. It's a harsh, realistic story, one that Bigelow honestly tells. Dark, subtle, intimate, epic, magnificent.
summary: Deserved Oscar for Best Picture, Screenplay, and Actress

reviewText: "Zero Dark Thirty" is the second collaboration between action director Kathryn Bigelow and journalist-turned-screenwriter Mark Boal. The duo seem to be the darlings of Hollywood, but I'm losing my taste for Kathryn Bigelow, whose work I have liked for 20 years, on account of this partnership. Boal's scripts are meaningless and impossible to direct effectively, so they show off Bigelow's abilities very poorly. "Zero Dark Thirty" purports to chronicle the CIA's 9 1/2-year manhunt for Osama bin Laden following his admission to being the mastermind behind the September 11, 2001 attacks on the World Trade Center and Pentagon. It focuses on the investigation by a relentless CIA analyst named "Maya", who is determined to locate and kill Bin Laden or, it seems, die trying.CIA analyst Maya (Jessica Chastain) travels to Pakistan, where a Saudi Arabian named Ammar (Reda Kateb) is being tortured by her colleague Dan (Jason Clarke), because Ammar is the nephew of someone who transferred $5000 to a 9/11 hijacker. Dan wants to know about planned terror attacks. Maya wants to know about a man named Abu Ahmed whom she believes is a courier with a direct line to Osama bin Laden. She's given an office in the embassy under the supervision of CIA station chief Joe Bradley (Kyle Chandler). Her immediate superior is a woman named Jessica (Jennifer Ehle), who is convinced that money motivates militant Islamists and can lead us to them. Maya, meanwhile, is obsessed with learning the identity of Abu Ahmed.This movie doesn't seem to be about anything. In fact, it seems to be trying very hard not to be about anything. The narrative is presented in a disjointed fashion, flitting around between Maya's obsessive search for Abu Ahmed, terror attacks, Washington, the inhospitable environment for Americans in Pakistan, strife between Maya and her superiors, another development in the Abu Ahmed investigation, more terror attacks, and so on. Critics have expressed a variety of opinions on how the film views torture, but the filmmakers try hard not to have a view on torture. Torture is presented in a fashion that makes even waterboarding seem mundane. It's effectively in the background."Zero Dark Thirty" implies that critical information about Abu Ahmed was discovered as a result of torture. It wasn't. It gives the impression that torture was used to extract specific pieces of information from people who were suspected of having that information. But that is not generally how the CIA or JSOC used torture. There is a scene in which a seemingly nice, educated man volunteers important information after, not during, being tortured, to avoid being tortured further. This makes no sense and did not happen. And, if you think that Ammar would not have been so easily fooled by Maya's attempt to trick him into spilling the beans in another scene, you're right. That scene is fictional. The place of torture in this narrative is fictional, but the film is indifferent to the act of torture.That's about as shrewd as "Zero Dark Thirty" gets in its attempts to manipulate the audience. Terror attacks around the globe are interspersed with the hunt for Osama bin Laden, giving the impression that the attacks had some connection to bin Laden or to his defunct organization in Afghanistan. Most had no such connection. That might qualify as an attempt to mislead in order to advance, or justify, a political agenda, but it seems more an attempt to bring some kind of urgency to a long, dull, disjointed story. The film's use of torture and terror attacks makes it sound like "Zero Dark Thirty" is an apologist or even cheerleader for the CIA's methods and goals in the post-9/11 years. But the CIA actually doesn't come across well at all, worst of all the story's protagonist.The CIA officers, as presented, are neither intelligent nor rational. They're yuppies. Their primary motivation seems to be careerism. They're given too much independence to pursue any theory that they think will get them a promotion. Jessica is irresponsible to the point of criminality. Dan is a caricature of an insecure macho male. Maya is a kook who tells her colleague that she believes she was "spared" so that she could "finish the job", i.e. kill bin Laden. She's a narcissist. Her station chief accuses her of being out of her mind and criticizes her obsession with bin Laden when homeland terrorism is not the current threat. So she has a temper tantrum. Maya is a socially maladjusted individual without any particular aptitude or appealing characteristic. Her defining qualities are her obsessiveness and self-delusion. I guess being a narcissistic dullard gets you far at the CIA.This is the movie's protagonist. She's a thoroughly distasteful character, despite the filmmakers' clumsy attempt to disguise that fact. They cast the sweet-voiced, pretty Jessica Chastain to make Maya more appealing. The result is that Chastain's mannerisms completely defy her dialogue, which comes off as ridiculous and not even a little convincing. It's such a blatant attempt to whitewash her that I just assumed that the real CIA analyst on which Maya is based must have a manner completely the opposite of Chastain's in the film. There is not one sympathetic character in this movie. They are pursuing Osama bin Laden, a person responsible for thousands of murders, yet there is no one to root for, as they are all two-dimensional and repellent. How can anyone write a film this badly?The raid on the compound in Abbottabad, Pakistan that took Osama bin Laden's life is presented in close to real time. The raid lasts 30 minutes, in the dark, including, inexplicably, 5 minutes watching the Navy SEALs collect harddrives and brick-a-brack in a bag. Too long. Total running time is 2 hours and 40 minutes. Way too long. If "Zero Dark Thirty" had been effective propaganda, it would have been entertaining and focused. If it had looked at the CIA's operations critically, it would have been thought-provoking. It's not trying to inform. It's not trying to propagandize beyond the little it needs to do to keep the White House happy. Its story-telling technique is dreadful. There is no character development. Even the title "Zero Dark Thirty" is trivial military slang, chosen to be meaningless. This film is badly written, badly directed, badly edited, badly cast, and badly acted.
summary: Irrespective of Politics, This Film Is Terrible.

reviewText: Much has been written about the torture scenes - if they really happened, if we should rely on torture as a reliable way to extract information and ultimately if we, as a freedom loving democracy, should even use torture. Every moviegoer can answer those questions in there own way. The movie certainly doesn't gloss over the torture scenes or make light of it.Beyond that the movie is riveting. The first 90 minutes concerns itself with the tedious but vital intelligence gathering in the 9 1/2 years leading up to locating OBL. The female CIA agent played by Jessica Chastain (The Help) works tirelessly on this. She becomes convinced that a minor player in Al Qaeda, a courier, is the way forward. She and a small group of covert agents tediously and painstakingly focus on the courier. When the courier's travels finally lead them to a reclusive walled in residence she reports this up the chain of command. Because she can not offer absolute certainity that OBL is the mysterious resident the bureaucrats and politicians above her pay grade become choked with caution. Days and weeks go by as the proper course of action is finalized. The last 45 minutes are intense as the Navy Seals make their move. This is where the movie shines.

reviewText: There may be spoilers.Director Kathryn Bigelow got everybody's attention in 2008 with "The Hurt Locker" and while this is certainly no sequel, there are some common elements that weave their way throughout both films.  Like Jeremy Renner's Sgt. James, Golden Globe winner Jessica Chastain's Maya is a bit of a loner.  Highly focused on their mission both characters have little use for nonsense.Maya is a CIA analyst recruited out of high school trained in the unglamorous work of sifting through leads to identify the whereabouts of Osama Bin Laden, beginning a couple years after 9/11.  Early on she joins a CIA interrogator (Jason Clarke) interviewing captured lower level terrorists.  The first 30 minutes of the film contains most of the well-documented torture scenes.  While unnerving, I didn't find them much more squirm inducing than when Daniel Craig as James Bond got his jollies wacked by a steel ball in "Casino Royale."In any case, a tidbit of info was revealed which Maya locks onto and runs with it for years, much to the dismay of her boss (Kyle Chandler) in Pakistan.  He and most everybody else believe the lead is worthless.  The middle section of the film can be a bit convoluted with the unfamiliar names in this part of the world and runs like an elaborate procedural investigation that we have now become familiar with.Bigelow and screenwriter Mark Boal used eyewitness accounts for the basis of their film and it certainly feels honest.  Chastain's casting is interesting.  A fair skinned redhead clearly stands out in the dusty Muslim world and Maya seems distant, even from those closest to her.  Not that she has a personal life.  She does get close to another female analyst (Jennifer Ehle) who becomes a casualty.  This leads to Maya's increased focus on the courier lead she had acquired years earlier.Maya learns to be tough and vocal about her beliefs in the macho world of the CIA.  In one great scene, her superiors are briefing the Secretary of Defense (James Gandolfini) who is to make a recommendation to President Obama as to whether they believe Osama is indeed holing up in a barricaded house in Abbottabad.  One by one the various agency heads hedge their bets by giving their odds of him being there.  Maya isn't asked but shouts out 100%.  She backs off to 95% and says something to the effect of "I know you guys don't like certainty."  When Secretary Panetta asks "who is this woman?" Maya responds "I'm the M.....f..... who found the place."  Memorable line.The third act begins as the seal team gets the go ahead for the assault.  Even though we know the outcome, Bigelow takes us through the precision flying though mountain passes and into the Osama compound.  The house is locked up tight so explosives are needed to take down doors and barricades.  This isn't one of those typical in-and-out missions.  It is done in real time (or at least so it seems).  This is one gripping film that ultimately is about one analyst's determination to get Osama Bin Laden.  Mission accomplished.
summary: 4 1/2 stars for a police procedural that turns into a gripping thriller

reviewText: With so many Bin Laden films now, documentaries, news specials, etc., the story has become trivialized and this movie continues in that vein.  It's focus on the psychotic tension of a young female CIA case officer whose only qualification is her ego-defining pursuit of fulfilling her will by killing Bin Laden may be seen by some as a woman filmmaker trying to boost the role of women in our conciousness but it fails.  You simply don't want to see this woman CIA case officer ever again by the time she lifts the body bag and looks on the dead face of a man her willfulness has killed in his bedroom.Was Bin Laden a monster, of course.  Was the Seal team highly trained and almost mythical as they walked between reality, fantasy, and history, without a doubt.  Was the intelligence community amazingly well-wired so as to catch even off hand comments and build from those back to an understanding of a world of criminals who thought they could hide in plain sight, absolutely.  Was the first Black President of the US on the line not only in the US but across the world after having toured the planet promising a new relationship while actually practicing what Richard Helms, David Atlee Phillips, and others had tried to do to Fidel Castro and maybe botching it so bad JFK ended up dead, incredibly so.None of that is in the film, only the willfulness of one young woman who when asked what else she had worked on for the CIA by James Gandolfini (in what will be his last remembered role as Leon Panetta) replied, "Nothing else, only this."  Well that may be enough for one person's ego or the glorification of that but it is not enough to make this film competitive with the other stories that come from this event in history.  Storytellers are not innocent and can confuse their own story with the one they are telling.  Better to be a filmmaker.

reviewText: I have to admit that I am a Navy SEAL junkie since the May 1, 2011, operation that resulted in the death of Usama Bin Laden in Pakistan. reviewText: What a stinker of a movie this was--I really wanted to like it--I waited in complete suspense for its' release. I can't believe it was nominated for even one Oscar.The acting was abominable; rote, wooden, uninspired, and cliched. Forty-five minutes into the movie, I kept wondering, "who cares about these characters, or even if they're historically accurate and portray 'real people' ?" The acting was just too mechanical and cliched to care.A shame. I really did want to enjoy this film. It's proof that a poor director with equally talentless actors/actresses can drag even the best subject matter down.Sure, we knew what was going to happen... I'd kept up with the 'hunt' for Al-Qaeda operatives, I knew beforehand all the AQ personalities that were mentioned. I followed the after-action news pretty intensely--just as I did with two-year investigation of Nixon and Watergate. Three masterful actors (Robards, Redford, and Hoffman) proved that one could take on an actual historical event of which the origins and outcome were known to the world (and where details were probably published even more thoroughly), and still, truly professional actors could craft great tension, suspense, and audience concern/interest for the characters they portrayed and the storyline even if it was already well-known.Not so with Bigelow and Chastain, et. al.  I was bored enough to check the time about 6x during the movie. I should have just given up and used the time more wisely. "Hurt Locker" wasn't worthy Oscar material in my mind, either, but at least there, the actors were inspired and skillful. It'll take one hell of a boring night for us to watch another Bigelow movie.Thankfully, we watched this as a rental. Back in the mail and good riddance!

reviewText: I'm a Kathryn Bigelow fan, going back to The Loveless, but ZD30 is a flat, strangely emotionless dud. Jessica Chastain chews scenery like it was her last meal - or alternately stares vaguely into space, which I guess is supposed to pass for thinking.The formal issue, of course, is  how to tell a story where everyone knows the ending. But as Raymond Chandler said, a good story is one you would read even if the ending was missing.The best moment is when a character describes the (current) president as a "thoughtful and analytical man" - and he's serious. There are a thousand wonderful and heartbreaking stories to be told about Afghanistan and Iraq. This isn't one of them.

reviewText: Watch Argo instead.This is full of Hollywood cliches and bad predictable writing, good signs of a true story right?Silly modern tough feminist slant and half ass political slants, that of course lead nowhere.I am so sick of modern big budget film studios afraid of making a solid stance on a subject that might offend someone or turn away potential ticket buyers.Disgusting torture, lame comedy, and lots foul language in a movie with a serious real life story (that many people around the world suffered from & are still suffering from) really leaves a bad taste in my mouth. reviewText: Katherine Bigelow is perhaps the best female action director on the planet, having a string is really great films to her credit dating back to the mid 80's. I think of her as sort of the Michael Mann of female directors. One of her best films is 'Point Break', one of the most exciting, stylish and action packed movies ever made, and she seems best fit to action pictures with lots of bells and whistles. And it was a wonder to behold when just recently her excellent film 'The Hurt Locker' won the best picture Oscar, and it was well deserved. You'd think the subject matter that comprised 'Zero Dark Thirty' would be right down her alley, and it actually is to some degree, but it's often a little too slow and there isn't a lot of action to speak of. The film does well in it's narative, and the acting, writing and plot are solid, it's just that there have been a couple of other films made on the same subject that were a lot more entertaining and just as well made, and were definately better movies. I believe Bigelow desired to tell a more accurate version of the events, and indeed has, but in doing so it made the entire afair seem a bit dull. Still it's a great film, but the feel of it just didn't stay with me. I didn't get the sense that it was one for the books, and I pretty much didn't even have any solid thoughts about it after I saw it.
summary: The same story told again in a less than entertaining manner

reviewText: Much has been made about the accuracy/inaccuracy of details contained in the film.  The picture is not a documentary, so if they bent the rules here and there, who can really complain?  The first half is excruciatingly boring, as it creates a map of intertwining terrorist scum bags, some of whom are tortured to reveal info about Osama bin Laden.  The scenes are not always very pleasant but have a realistic edginess to them.  At about the halfway mark the film switches gears and finally becomes something like a docu-drama, with plenty of tension and action.  The film should have spent less time connecting terrorist dots, and more time on the team who would infiltrate Osama's little fortress and eliminate his life.  The malfeasance of the CIA was interesting, as was the many small errors made on the night of the raid.
summary: An Average or Slightly Above-Average Film

reviewText: The first half of Zero Dark Thirty is pretty confusing. So many Arab names. So many pieces of the puzzle to track. We start right in with the torture, and it is not fun. Gradually as many threads lead to dead ends, we start to get a more coherent picture. The narrative is punctuated by numerous terrorist bombings. Sometimes you know the explosion is coming, because you're familiar with the incident. But you never know exactly when, and each time it's a heart-stopping shock. Scenes of wandering through urban areas of Pakistan looking for a suspect are appropriately chaotic. And when we finally get to the raid on Bin Laden's compound, the mood is admirably reserved. No music through any of it, just terse commands and lots of night-vision shots. Jessica Chastain is convincing as Maya, the one who sees the search through from beginning to end. James Gandolfini is perfect as Leon Panetta, the CIA Director (although he is not named in the movie other than "CIA Director", similarly, Maya only has a first name). Especially haunting is the final scene, when Maya boards a plane back to the States and it's clear she has no idea what she's going to do now.
summary: Riveting tale of how it went down

reviewText: I liked it and would recommend it, but I didn't get a feel for any of the characters.  It was as if they were all robots of political or espionage machinery.  At least one character made mention of getting away from the grind of interrogation, but it was kind of off-hand throwaway comment.  He never really seemed tired or exhausted or even much annoyed by what he did - he just went at it like a machine.Probably to really give it the depth the story really needed it would've needed to be a 5-hour, BBC-style, TV drama with each "part" of the story getting it's own slice of time.  I know that seemingly makes no sense given my title review, but because the characters were so 1-dimensional the pacing dragged. I think if there was more depth, then the time required to add depth would've made it longer but it would've *felt* shorter.So anyways... for a pseudo-documentary/drama of the events that may or may not have happened just like portrayed, it was good.

reviewText: This film is a far cry from the pro-Obama propaganda that many conservatives were concerned it would be. Instead it has become controversial w/the liberals for its favorable treatment of the CIA's use of enhanced interrogation techniques...which they of course call torture. While intelligence was gathered through a variety of techniques, it can be argued with some credibility that bin Laden would not have been found when he was w/out enhanced interrogation. While this is a powerful portrayal of the hunt for bin Laden - probably the best portrayal we will ever see on film - it is not for the squeamish. Torture or not, enhanced interrogation is difficult to watch; and you will hear pervasive profanity, and see explicit violence perpetrated by terrorists and our own people. If you choose not to watch it though, you will miss an outstanding espionage film and piece of our recent history; and you will miss a tour de force performance by Jessica Chastain, whose character, Maya, is patterned after a real CIA operative...the operative who is credited more than any other w/smoking out bin Laden. Katheryn Bigelow performs masterfully behind the camera...was anyone but me surprised this was directed by a woman? This movie is an outstanding example of the cinematic art.
summary: "I'm going to smoke everyone involved in this op and then I'm going to kill Osama bin Laden."

reviewText: Zero Dark Thirty(released Dec/12)stars,among others,Jessica Chastain as Maya,Jason Clarke as Dan,Joel Edgerton as Patrick,Chris Pratt as Justin,Mark Strong as George,Jennifer Ehle as Jessica,andKyle Chandler as Joseph Bradley.The potential for a super movie was all there:great cast,locations and the ultimate point of capturing a top terrorist.Unfortunately the plot/editing and too much attention to detail,derails this film before it has an even chance of getting off the ground.The Reader's Digest version of this film intro's us to a CIA agent(Chastain)who has been working on getting Osama Bin Laden for 12 years,and nothing else.She shows up at a detainee center,first as an observer then as an active participant.Time passes in years as bombings start occurring around the world,post 9/11.They can only glean so much information out of their "methods of persuasion",and when Bush is replaced by Obama,the detainee program quickly comes to a halt.The bombings continue,even one that kills a close friend of Chastain's in a compound in Afghanistan.Chastain makes very slow head way through it all with her superiors,but keeps pushing with a lead that to her is the best in many years.When the intel piles up to such a great degree,then and only then,is she finally able to get a go ahead for a mission.Two stealth copters will invade a compound in Islamabad where she believes Bin Laden and some underlings are hiding out.The operation goes through and is a success.Bin Laden is killed and his body brought back for an ID by Chastain.The movie ends as Chastain hops aboard a transport she has all to herself and sits down,totally exhausted.The long story?.....well you will have to watch the movie yourself.And at 150 or so minutes this thing is a LONG trek.....TOO long.I found myself watch watching more than a few times.The film takes us inexorably through the interrogating of prisoners(water boarding and the like),Chastains inability to make any headway with her bosses above her,the bombings around the world year after year,the change in the political landscape which directly affects their ability to gain intel,and on and on.The movie does pick up slightly when they finally invade the compound of Bin Laden,but even that is very slow moving with no real excitement built in.The thing is with a film like this:we know beforehand the outcome and all the incidents leading up to the finale.The trick for the director and script writers on a movie of this type is how interesting are you going to make it in order to grab my attention away from what I already know? It's like say the TV series The Band of Brothers.The record of that outfit was well known and written about,but the creators made it so interesting and compelling it was bound to be an instant hit.This film,I'm sorry to say,does not even come close to approaching that find of film making.The makers of Zero Dark Thirty failed to do what they had to do to get the job done.Technically speaking the film is in its w/s a/r of 1:85:1 and is clear and crisp.Extras include four featurettes.All in all a big disappointment.The film's creators failed to create any kind of excitement or compelling reason to be apathetic to material we all knew the background on in advance.Watching paint dry?......you bet.2 1/2- 3 stars.

reviewText: ****1/2“Zero Dark Thirty” chronicles one of the greatest successful manhunts of all time - the one that resulted in the death of Osama bin Laden in Pakistan on May 1, 2011. With a screenplay by Mark Boal and direction by Kathryn Bigelow, the movie provides a methodical, step-by-step re-enactment of the decade-long hunt as seen through the eyes of Maya Lambert, a fictional CIA analyst who is actually a composite of several female analysts who played key roles in locating the ever-elusive al Qaeda leader.Much has been made of the fact that the movie seemingly endorses the view that the use of torture led to the discovery of bin Laden’s whereabouts. This assertion caused such a controversy at the time of the movie’s release that many felt it ultimately hurt its chances of walking home with the Best Picture Oscar that year. In all fairness to the moviemakers, however, the film actually doesn’t seem to be making that case, since the scenes early on depicting torture all lead to eventual dead ends, while the piece of information that initially sets the investigators onto the right path clearly comes much later, after torture is no longer being used as a tactic. Yet, had the filmmakers NOT shown torture being used in the early stretches of the film - which take place not too long after 9/11 - they would not have been truthful to the times in which the story is set.But it is as a drama that we must ultimately judge “Zero Dark Thirty” - and, in that respect, the news is mainly positive. The movie stays intensely focused on the matter at hand, not allowing itself to get distracted by side forays into too many irrelevant factors or overly-detailed character back stories. Yet, while this is generally a virtue, it does result in a certain weakness as well, mainly, a lack of depth in the characters, particularly the main one. One need only compare “Zero Dark Thirty” to something like Showtime‘s “Homeland” to see the advantages the long-form format has over the short-form when dealing with subjects as complex as this one. And one need only compare ZDT’s Maya with “Homeland”s Carrie (Claire Danes) to see how much more fully developed the latter is as a character. Maya is allowed to register fear, anger, frustration, determination, disappointment, etc., but we never feel that we really get to know her as a person. For one thing, we never see her in a single relationship with anyone other than her colleagues (or even hear of one mentioned, come to think of it), even though the movie spans nearly a decade.That being said, the movie does convey, through Jessica Chastain’s riveting performance, the very real toll exacted on individuals who dedicate their lives to a dogged pursuit of terrorists and who feel heavily the burden of heading off any attacks in the future. Perhaps the lack of any reference to Maya’s personal life is an implicit acknowledgment of that fact. Regardless, Chastain provides so luminous a beacon for us to follow along the journey that we can’t help but connect with the pursuit on a deeply human level.Chastain gets strong support from Jason Clark, Kyle Chandler, Jennifer Ehle, James Gandolfini and Chris Pratt (“Everwood,” “Parks and Recreation”)  in the atypical role (for him) of a heroic Navy Seal.In fact, the movie’s meticulous re-enactment of the Navy Seals’ successful raid on the Abbottabad compound is alone worth the price of admission. It really does make us feel as if we were a part of history.

reviewText: Who knew the hunt for Osama bin Laden could be this boring?  The film is long -- almost 3 hours -- and you have to sit through two tedious hours of incomprehensible, seemingly pointless interrogation and torture before the story gains any real traction. (This would have been better served as a straight documentary, although even for a documentary it lacks punch.) It is nigh impossible from most of the proceedings here to ascertain how the CIA actually located Bin Laden.  Jessica Chastain was nominated for an Oscar for her role in the film, and does an adequate job, although basically she is miscast.  And the role doesn't allow for any dramatic latitude, and degenerates into melodramatic shouting toward the end.  James Gandolfini appears briefly, and is also miscast.  So after sitting through more than two hours that drag on endlessly, you must then be subjected to an overlong, protracted sequence in which the Navy SEALs storm the compound and kill Bin Laden.  Not surprisingly, even this sequence lacks a sense of tension and excitement.  Someone keeps forgetting to tell Kathryn Bigelow that a movie needs to have some sort of dramatic arc.  Although "The Hurt Locker" fared better than this, it suffered from the same lack of story arc.
summary: A major disappointment.  Overlong, and deadly boring.

reviewText: Based on the title, I expected the movie to focus on the attack on OBL's compound in Allahabad.  Instead, the attack occupied only the last 30 minutes or so of the movie.  No mention was made of the intense preparation by the SEALs prior to the operation.  A more realistic, descriptive title would have been "The Hunt for Bin Laden."I had major challenges with the depiction of CIA personnel.  During my 30-year Army career as a field artilleryman, I spent 12 years overseas including a combat tour in Vietnam and tours of duty as dense attaché in Dhaka, Bangladesh, as a lieutenant colonel and later as a colonel in New Delhi.  In both attaché assignments, I had close professional and personal relationships with the station chiefs and case officers.  These selfless Americans were generally much better mannered than the characters portrayed in the movie.  I found the profane language excessive and unrealistic.  I am not a prude, and I realize that during times of duress, folks resort to foul language that they would not necessary use on a routine basis.  But, I felt that the overuse of the F-bomb was uncalled for and did not depict how intelligence professionals actually conduct themselves.  The CIA officer in charge of the "enhanced" interrogation came across as unprofessional and somewhat cowboyish.While the defense attaché in New Delhi, I worked with members of JSOC during a prolonged hostage situation in Kashmir in 1995.  I also knew several SEALs who had left active duty and were working with for another government agency. All of these outstanding young Americans were world-class athletes, generally quiet, reflective, and totally committed to mission accomplishment.  The movie was entertaining, but I wish it had been more true to its title in order to truly recognize the achievements of these great warriors.

reviewText: If you'd like to see multiple scenes of torture convincingly depicted on-screen, this is the one to view.If you'd care to know exactly how Bin Laden's compound in Pakistan appeared on the day he was assassinated (right down to intricate designs in ceramic floor-tiles), watch the Blu-ray supplementary material. The production designers recreated the compound, full-scale, in exquisite detail at great expense. But unfortunately, since these few crucial and climactic minutes of the movie were filmed mostly in the dark, you won't be able to enjoy them in the movie per se: less than five per cent of it is visible, I'd estimate, and even that is presented dimly, in sickly green or yellow light. Yes, this may be the way the SEALs experienced it at thirty minutes past midnight. But it's so dark in the film, it's almost ludicrous. It might as well have been filmed at a Holiday Inn somewhere in Nevada for all you're able to see. What a colossal waste of first-class production design.Except for that, it's an excellent movie from the hands of highly talented movie makers.

reviewText: Kathryn Bigelow's Zero Dark Thirty is a controversial, button pushing account of the manhunt and eventual assassination of Osama bin Laden and just how it all came to be. One's politics will most likely play a substancal role in their enjoyment of this film, I find far too few people are able to put such things aside.However, Zero Dark Thirty  wisely neither condemns nor condoles the actions of the CIA and United States military, it takes more of a journalist's eye view to it's subject matter, it is detached from it`s material. It is also a completely engrossing and engulfing, well paced crackerjack of a thriller that doesn't strive to please or entertain per se, but manages to do both quite nicely all the same.Told as a step by step procedural of the CIA's actions and involvement in the manhunt for bin Laden. But the focus is on the single minded resolve of the woman who courageously and audaciously led the hunt. This is one film that can't be critized for not providing a strong female character. As Maya, the determined CIA agent Jessica Chastain once more gives a strong and absorbing performance, she has been nominated for an Oscar for this role, her second in as many years. For my money she deserves the award, but most likely will not get it,  playing a strong, defiant and independent woman and not reducing her to a cliché action hero, damsel in distress or even attempting to make her a likable protagonist, she simply has a job to do and don't get in her way.All of this told through Bigelow's finely honed lens, previously only a good director of mostly routine and forgettable potboilers like Point Break  and Blue Steel, but also the underappreciated Strange Days and the excellent vampire/psychos on the open road neo-western Near Dark. In 2010 she became the surprise first woman to win an Academy Award for directing, which she richly deserved for the superb the Hurt Locker. Reteaming here with her Hurt Locker collaborator screenwriter Mark Boal, they have a riveting movie chemistry for making great dramatic thrillers.Zero Dark Thirty wants to be a conversation piece, it wants to make you uncomfortable The fact that it is also so entertaining is beside the point. The torture scenes, which have been much a source of debate, are graphic and unpleasant, which seems appropriate. The camerawork is not flashy, nor is it intrusive, it wisely serves as little more than just a bystander or as a witness.The dialogue is tough sounding, but realistic to the ears. Boal writes like a reporter, everything sounds over heard. The meetings with high ranking officals give us the feeling of a fly on the wall with top security clearance.The late French film critic and auteur filmmaker of the finest order Francois Truffett was quoted as saying that the best way to critize a movie was with the making of another movie. This used to be a favorite saying of Roger Ebert on the old Siskel & Ebert at the Movies TV show. I am surprised that so few have drawn any comparisons with the critically lambasted Act of Valor. In case you don't remember that one, it's the movie released earlier in 2012 that stared real life Marines in a fictional propaganda adventure film. It looked like an Army recruitment commercial, "be all you can be", "it`s not a job, it`s an adventure", etc. Zero Dark Thirty mages to be serious, where Act of Valor was silly, one is unflinching and ugly, the other a shameful misinformative ad.Bigelow it would seem now makes the hard hitting topical films that Oliver Stone used to make, someone like say John Wayne or Ronald Reagon would have loved Act of Valor, but would have been appalled by Zero Dark Thirty's resolute neo-patriotism.Zero Dark Thirty also serves as the greatest celebration of intelligence in the movies of late. Not just of government intelligence, but of the individual's hard work and dogged determination.The best movies of 2012 have also been the most controversial, From Tarantino's Django Unchained to Ben Affleck's Argo and the under seen Cloud Atlas. 2012 was a year that brought a lot of thoughts to movie screens, a lot of discussions raised, no easy answers to be found. I can't remember a year when so many films pushed so many boundaries and ran the risk of offending and alienating so many.But it is good to see so many thoughts put out there, so many daring films made and so many willing filmmakers. Maybe we are entering a new era where the term "a thinking person's movie" wont be meet with automatic scorn and fear from the masses. Then again, I could be wrong.The first thing we see on screen is a promise that what we are about to see is based on actual first hand accounts. One of the many sources of controversy and speculation. Some critics have laid the claimed that it is fabricated , or at least to some degree. Just a few months ago Fox news pundits claimed Bigelow had been given classified information in the making of this film(?). Oh well, it's tight and taunt and one thriller worth getting worked up about. Zero Dark Thirty is one movie that wont be forgotten, it's a new classic that we have been privileged of witnessing being born.see my reviews at moviezonemagazine.com

reviewText: I missed Zero Dark Thirty in the theaters and decided to get a copy. reviewText: There was so much hype around this film I expected it to be much better than it was. Besides the fact that this film doesn't really tell you anything you haven't already heard from the mainstream media nor does it go so far as to explore anything as they did in "Body of Lies" it actually makes Americans look like a bunch of ruthless myopic wankers. Here's the  basic run down: Hard nosed ambitious CIA chick is obsessed with finding Bin Laden, its her job and she's passionate about it yada yada yada. They torture a few people at Gitmo or some US black site to get the intel yada  yada yada and then she has a hunch follows the hunch and she finds & kills OBL, she's then seen crying on the plane leaving Afghanistan screen goes to black. reviewText: I'm not an expert on the events that lead to the discovery and eventual killing of Bin Laden. I know some details of the actual raid and events that happened after, but the effort that went into finding his hide out are all new to me. With that being said, Zero Dark Thirty is a fine piece of cinematic craftsmanship and a excellent espionage thriller. The film follows the efforts a female CIA agent named Maya who has made it her life's work to find and kill Bin Laden. We follow her as she assists in torturing captives, tracks down leads(some with results, most without) and slowly puts the pieces of a very complex and frustrating puzzle together. As the film progressed, I couldn't help but feel Maya's frustration. The film sticks to the script quite well, and we're made to follow Maya down every road she takes, whether that road leads to a break in the case or it's filled with road blocks or a dead end.Zero Dark Thirty does it's best to stick to the details, but it's a process that can leave many people in the dark(no pun intended) The process of discovering and following up on leads is a tedious one, viewers excepting an action packed film maybe disappointed. The film isn't without it's moments of pulse pounding tension. When Maya finally follows the lead that results in Bin Laden's discovery, the film's pace accelerates tremendously.As a casual viewer(i'm not a current events buff)I enjoyed Zero Dark Thirty immensely. I did find the first third of the film to be a little tedious but I think that's what Kathryn Bigelow and Co. were aiming for. The process of finding and eliminating Bin Laden was a slow and tedious process that wasn't very glamorous. The scenes of torture were left open to interpretation. I felt that the film wasn't pro or anti torture, but it was trying to show an honest portrayal of what the US was willing to do. The film wasn't trying to make a statement or be preachy, which I find to be a difficult task considering the subject matter. Zero Dark Thirty is an excellent film and one of the best films of the year.

reviewText: The trailer that's all over TV for Zero Dark Thirty gives the impression that the movie might document Navy SEAL Team 6's prep and execution of the mission in May 2011 that got Osama bin Laden. However, I was surprised to find that that the 2  hour runtime of the film was much more about the other heroes...the heroes involved in the investigation and decade-long hunt for the diabolical al-Qaeda terrorist kingpin.The 2  hours actually went by quite quickly. Director Kathryn Bigelow did a tremendous job of keeping the information flow interesting, disturbing, unsettling, exciting and seemingly very real. I felt like a fly on the wall watching the grueling 10-year investigation in a matter of hours. And the lead actors really earned all of the accolades for making the viewer feel like they were watching footage of some amazing, horrible but actual events.Ultimately, the movie does conclude with one of the most memorable, intense and captivating 30 - 45 minutes of a movie that I've ever watched as SEAL Team 6 does their thing. But it is the entire 10 year process that is presented expertly in Zero Dark Thirty makes this film so deserved of all of the critical nominations and essential viewing for all.

reviewText: Well with 396 reviews here already, as I post this, (many from the theatrical release), I'm certainly not the first but I hope I can add a few helpful comments about the DVD version of the film.First off, I will say that I liked the film a lot. No, not the graphic violence, but that can't be helped with a story on the subject that this film is all about. But it did fill in the story during the 10 year period from 9/11/2011 until 2011 when Osama bin Laden was found and killed.Usually the Bluray is the only version with extra bonus features. But this time the DVD contains about 25 minutes worth. There is neither Director's commentary nor even the film's "trailer" but here are the four "bonuses:No small feat - the "making of" featurette narrated mostly by Director Kathryn Bigelow. But it's waaaaay too short at just 3:52.The Compound - this 9-minute featurette focuses on the bin Laden compound where he was discovered and where the final 30 minutes of the 2 -hour film takes place. The replicated set was built in Jordan in three weeks and Producer/Screenwriter Mark Boal takes the viewer on a guided tour of the set. This is well worth seeingGeared Up - is a 7-minute featurette that shows how the actors were trained by Navy Seals in the mission and reveals that some of the crew in those final scenes were actual  former serviceman.Targeting Jessica Chastain - is the weakest feature. It's 5 minutes of the cast talking about how good an actress Chastain is in the role of Maya.What's missing here - besides a longer "making of" feature is the story behind the real life Maya character - the young CIA agent who set out to find bin Laden and capture him - dead or alive.This is not a film to watch before you go to bed - there are too many strong images. But I'm glad I watched it.I hope this review is both informative and helpful.Steve Ramm"Anything Phonographic"
summary: Review of the DVD and list of "special features"

reviewText: Can you make a good movie from a bad script? Yes, and that movie is called Zero Dark Thirty.Most of the film is the informative, though poorly told, story of a young woman at the CIA whose job and obsession is to find Osama Bin Laden. We are given vital pieces of information, and experience the frustrations, of this global manhunt. Along the way, unfortunately, the petty `n' plucky heroine has to constantly assert herself as correct. She just thinks something is so, and then it becomes right. She is so infallible that it is both exhausting and eye-rolling to watch her. She is also so arrogant it makes her impossible to root for; in the film's most ludicrous line, she states that she believes her colleagues died and she survived because she is "meant" to find Bin Laden. What?Fortunately, it all comes together in the last 30 minutes or so. The climax, a retelling of the operation that killed Bin Laden, is so well told and thrilling that it almost makes up for the rest of the film. Better yet, the information we were told throughout the film (what is Bin Laden's complex like? who will be there?) helps orient us during what is an otherwise dark and jerky sequence. This was a prime example of quality filmmaking, which most of the movie could not live up to.There has been much controversy over the film's torture sequences; I personally did not find much stock in them, but that is up to the viewer to decide. What I found interesting was how it didn't seem to take much for interrogators to resort to waterboarding; whether that is fiction or fact, I don't know.Which is what makes my critique of the film a bit reserved - without knowing the facts, I don't know how far I can criticize the film. Maybe Jessica Chastain's character really was right, all the time, always. Even if she was, though, that's not how you make a movie. I like my protagonists with a touch of fallibility, and Zero Dark Thirty does not meet this base requirement.

reviewText: A dozen years since the worst attack on American soil, a back story of what may have lead to the killing of Osama Bin Laden and a meaningful strike against Al Qaeda is presented in "Zero Dark Thirty".  The storyline is meticulously woven with broadly reported events and high production values and wrapped in Director Kathryn Bigelow's reportage style of cinematography.  We are present during supposed meetings, black ops and interrogations that will never be de-classifed, to understand what our government has been doing to recover some sense of control over our homeland security, providing us a sense of the anguish and sacrifice made in the struggle.  We get news coverage and clippings from available sources, but this movie gives us a chance to feel like we're peeking behind the curtain.  Even without the focus on the feminine contributions to what's been achieved, this is a gripping and believable film effort.

reviewText: Forget the "superhero" stories, this movie documents the grizzly side of the American search for bin Laden -- nothing is disallowed, to hell with human rights, international Conventions, rules of law, or human decency.We see not only how the subjects of torture are dehumanized, but also the torturers themselves.  Hardened by the work they volunteered for, they become the animals they accuse the objects of their scorn of being.Into this setting in Afghanistan/Pakistan, drops a young woman (Maya) who we see transformed from the technocrat she trained as into as much an animal as the men around her.When another woman is deceived into taking the bait, in her own quest for career glory, her death by car bomb has a more immediate impact on Maya than on her male colleagues.  This death makes Maya even more determined to follow her instincts about who will lead them to bin Laden's hideout.  But she needs "resources" from head office in Washington in order to pursue the lead, and is prepared to play every card available to get them.This movie is relentless, spell-binding, and much is shown in semi-darkness to keep you guessing.You'll be thinking about this film long after seeing it.

reviewText: Like Helen of Troy who "launched a thousand ships", the 9/11 attacks launched two $1 trillion wars in Iraq and Afghanistan.  As a civil obligation, people should know the 9/11 events and aftermath --  whether you prefer to inform yourself through the variety of "news shows" or documentaries, or be entertained in the process (like this movie), this is important current history.  Given the hundreds of reviews, I can't add more to them.  The film is 2 parts --  the 10-year manhunt and the take-down.  Typically, viewers complained about the slow pace of the manhunt that resulted in a dead end.  The take-down is often described as riveting.This is not an action-thriller, but a "docu-drama" so I don't know how the director (Kathryn Bigelow, an ex- of James Cameron, an insufferable but talented director) could deliver anything more than what she did.The ramp-up to the mission was too long ? . . . well, my takeaway is that the director wanted to us to see that after something like 10-years and apparently no leads for 4-6 years, the US establishment looking for bin Laden became fatigued, lackadaisical or less audacious, and it took some low grade analyst(s) and mid-level bosses to undertake career ending moves to get a mission approved, and fulfilled something reportedly said to bin Laden when the 9/11 attacks happened: "If you did that to the Americans, they will hunt you down and kill you." (or something like that).Along with being an interesting film, there are also interesting film making stories:  it brought Megan Ellison, then 26-year old trust fund daughter of Larry Ellison of Oracle Software, recognition as movie producer that she typically avoids; how they recruited Jessica Chastain for the Maya role which Ms. Chastain could not at first accept; and even as a movie about the most signicant person/event/episode in American History since December 7, 1941, funding for this movie was not a big sell.  This is a fantastic effort to artistically record (although Mark Boal, the reporter & screen writer would prefer technical acknowledgement) this generation's most significant event which will still impact the US for many years to come.  The recent book publication of "The Wrong Enemy" provides a bit of the Vietnam War's "Gulf of Tonkin" which is "If only we knew, we would have done things differently" (and potentially saved $2 trillion and 200,000 civilian lives).
summary: Civil Duty to Know the Events Depicted

reviewText: This is a great account of perhaps the most important man hunt in American history which took a decade of patience and plotting and instinctive speculation on part of a focused and obsessive CIA operative. The film covers the Navy SEAL Team 6 operation of May 2011 that killed Usama Bin Laden. Kathryn Bigelow has come out with another thriller after her brilliant `Hurt Locker' which shot Jeremy Renner into fame. This film has another impressive performance by Jessica Chastain as Maya, the CIA operative in Pakistan. This was the best performance by an actress in 2012. She was not even nominated. Meryl Streep was awarded for `The Iron Lady', playing Margaret Thatcher. Maybe, that was an author backed role and the jury tends to tilt towards such performances but Chastain's was the more sensitive one. A great statement by Kathryn Bigelow. She has got style. Chastain was acknowledged by the Broadcast Film Critics Association as the best actress. She is a versatile actress. I was impressed by her performance as Maggie Beauford in `Lawless'. As Maya in this film, she has done a strong portrayal of a stubborn and obstinate CIA operative who targets the couriers that Laden was using while working on a base from Abbottabad, Pakistan.
summary: A great account of perhaps the most important manhunt in American history

reviewText: Saw Zero Dark Thirty and was not impressed.It centres around a woman CIA operative (Jessica Chastain) who works on location in Pakistan and Afghanistan pursuing Osama Bin Laden through the use of torture.She observes torture and is at first seen to flinch,but she soon seems able to accept it.Because she's a female heroine and not an action hero,we do not get the gung-ho approach of male directors.As a feminist she cools the subject using a woman.The film's opening,dark screen and phone call from a woman trapped in the Twin Towers about to burn to death.Then the film flips immediately into scenes of torture as in cause and effect.Because we have been assured the film is "based on first person accounts" and that Bigelow herself said to depict it is not to endorse it,we are made to feel we are getting the `first draft of history',a journalistic account,but it's claimto apolitical neutrality is false.Bigelow is for the patriotic status quo.This is a CIA-biased film,right wing to the core.It achieves its objective to give some meaning to the killing of Osama Bin Laden by showing terrorist attacks following 9/11(Khobar Towers,the Islamabad Marriott)as well as the unbridled CIA response.The war on terror is seen as justified revenge.At the `black sites' CIA investigators like Dan(Jason Clarke) seek information about the whereabouts of the al-Qaeda leader,using soft and hard techniqueslike water-boarding or giving a soft drink to the suspect,treating him like a dog or chatting to him like a mate.To depict torture neutrally is already a kind of endorsement.Bigelow is shown to be on the side of torture. Maya loses friends in the field.Her fanaticalpursuit of Bin Laden helps to neutralise moral qualms.Bigelow eases liberal guilt by showing the effect on the torturer's sensitivity,Maya pays a cost,having no love or relationships.Our instincts tell us there is something wrong here.To normalise torture(we see Obama saying they don't use torture),is to remove ethical principles.It directly implies the use of torure led directly to the location of OBL(Abbadabad).That said the thriller/action techniques of Bigelow(as proved in Hurt Locker),the film editing/writing are good,the chapter-like structure,the casting of Chastain where her intelligence is underscored by a ferocious determination," I believed I was spared so I could finish the job".This is an emotionless and cold-hearted film so much so that the climactic raid has no energy or urgency,the role of the Navy Seals is de-emphasised,ciphers in a computer game.Sorry Syriana and Homeland did this so much better.Chastain does not carry the moral weight.

reviewText: This film is about Maya (Jessica Chastain) a potty mouthed CIA operative and her one woman crusade to get Bin Laden. It starts off with 9-11. Maya is a composite character. The CIA is not as dumb as this film portrays. She visits CIA black sites around the world through their revolving door. It appears as if she got all the intelligence on her own. We know this was not the case.In comparison, I must say "Seal Team Six" was a far better film as far as plot. What this film offers is an obsessed Jessica Chastain who borders on insanity. Her character seemed unrealistic at times, but compelling at other times.Much has been made about the politics of this film which I found they took great lengths to be non-controversial. Sometimes facts have a bias to them. There is excessive torture at the beginning of the film. Information is gathered from people that have been tortured, but not necessarily because of it, as there is a disconnect between the two events. The audience is allowed to decide on its effectiveness. Seal Team Six appears late in the film, almost as an afterthought. The other film was superior in presenting the Navy Seals.Obama and Bush aren't mentioned per se. Obama appears speaking in the background on TV. There is a new policy concerning torture that is alluded to, but the details are not given. One remark was, "You don't want to be the one caught holding the dog collar."There is a reluctance on the part of some to invade the Bin Laden compound due to the WMD/Iraq disaster although no blame is specifically placed.Chastain does an excellent job and is the best aspect of this feature. In an idea world she would have played Maya in "Seal Team Six." I found the political criticisms unwarranted as was the praise given to this film when "Seal Team Six" was clearly the superior production in presenting the tale. If you haven't caught "Seal Team Six" check it out.Recap: Chastain great. Rest of movie so-so. "Seal Team Six" superior over-all.Parental guidance: F-bombs, no sex, some male prisoner rear nudity.
